scope="row" style="padding-right: 0.5em;">Website</th><td style="line-height: 1.35em;"><span class="url"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://www.spacex.com">www<wbr />.spacex<wbr />.com</a></span></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" style="text-align:center;line-height: 1.35em;"><b>Footnotes&#160;/&#32;references</b><br /><sup id="cite_ref-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-3">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-4">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-5">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-6">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup></td></tr></tbody></table>\n<p><b>Space Exploration Technologies Corp.</b>, trading as <b>SpaceX</b>, is a <a href="/wiki/Private_company" class="mw-redirect" title="Private company">private</a> American <a href="/wiki/Aerospace_manufacturer" title="Aerospace manufacturer">aerospace manufacturer</a> and <a href="/wiki/Space_transportation" class="mw-redirect" title="Space transportation">space transportation</a> services company headquartered in <a href="/wiki/Hawthorne,_California" title="Hawthorne, California">Hawthorne, California</a>. It was founded in 2002 by <a href="/wiki/Elon_Musk" title="Elon Musk">Elon Musk</a> with the goal of reducing space transportation costs to enable the <a href="/wiki/Colonization_of_Mars" title="Colonization of Mars">colonization of Mars</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-NYT-20160927_7-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-NYT-20160927-7">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-:6_8-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:6-8">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-9" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-9">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup> SpaceX has developed <a href="/wiki/SpaceX_launch_vehicles" title="SpaceX launch vehicles">several launch vehicles</a> and the <a href="/wiki/SpaceX_Dragon" title="SpaceX Dragon">Dragon</a> spacecraft.\n</p><p>SpaceX\'s achievements include the first privately funded <a href="/wiki/Liquid-propellant_rocket" title="Liquid-propellant rocket">liquid-propellant rocket</a> to reach orbit (<a href="/wiki/Falcon_1" title="Falcon 1">Falcon 1</a> in 2008),<sup id="cite_ref-sfn20080928_10-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-sfn20080928-10">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup> the first private company to successfully launch, orbit, and recover a spacecraft (<a href="/wiki/SpaceX_Dragon" title="SpaceX Dragon">Dragon</a> in 2010), the first private company to send a spacecraft to the <a href="/wiki/International_Space_Station" title="International Space Station">International Space Station</a> (Dragon in 2012),<sup id="cite_ref-NYT-20120525_11-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-NYT-20120525-11">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup> the first <a href="/wiki/VTVL" title="VTVL">propulsive landing</a> for an orbital rocket (<a href="/wiki/Falcon_9" title="Falcon 9">Falcon 9</a> in 2015), the first reuse of an orbital rocket (Falcon 9 in 2017), and the first private company to launch an object into <a href="/wiki/Heliocentric_orbit" title="Heliocentric orbit">orbit around the sun</a> (<a href="/wiki/Falcon_Heavy" title="Falcon Heavy">Falcon Heavy</a>\'s payload of a <a href="/wiki/Elon_Musk%27s_Tesla_Roadster" title="Elon Musk&#39;s Tesla Roadster">Tesla Roadster</a> in 2018). SpaceX has flown 18 resupply missions to the International Space Station (ISS) under a partnership with <a href="/wiki/NASA" title="NASA">NASA</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-nsf20150515_12-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsf20150515-12">&#91;12&#93;</a></sup> NASA also awarded SpaceX <a href="/wiki/Commercial_Crew_Development" title="Commercial Crew Development">a further development contract</a> in 2011 to develop and demonstrate a <a href="/wiki/Human-rating_certification" title="Human-rating certification">human-rated</a> Dragon, which would be used to transport astronauts to the ISS and return them safely to Earth.<sup id="cite_ref-13" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-13">&#91;13&#93;</a></sup> SpaceX conducted the maiden launch of its <a href="/wiki/Dragon_2" title="Dragon 2">Dragon 2</a> spacecraft on a NASA-required demonstration flight (<a href="/wiki/Crew_Dragon_Demo-1" title="Crew Dragon Demo-1">Crew Dragon Demo-1</a>) on March 2, 2019 and is set to launch its first crewed Dragon 2 in March 2020.<sup id="cite_ref-14" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-14">&#91;14&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-15" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-15">&#91;15&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-16" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-16">&#91;16&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>In December 2015, a <a href="/wiki/Falcon_9" title="Falcon 9">Falcon 9</a> accomplished a propulsive <a href="/wiki/VTVL" title="VTVL">vertical landing</a>. This was the first such achievement by a rocket for <a href="/wiki/Orbital_spaceflight" title="Orbital spaceflight">orbital spaceflight</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-guardian20151222_17-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-guardian20151222-17">&#91;17&#93;</a></sup> In April 2016, with the launch of <a href="/wiki/CRS-8" class="mw-redirect" title="CRS-8">CRS-8</a>, SpaceX successfully vertically landed the first stage on an ocean <a href="/wiki/Autonomous_spaceport_drone_ship" title="Autonomous spaceport drone ship">drone ship</a> landing platform.<sup id="cite_ref-guardian20160408_18-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-guardian20160408-18">&#91;18&#93;</a></sup> In May 2016, in another first, SpaceX again landed the first stage, but during a significantly more energetic <a href="/wiki/Geostationary_transfer_orbit" title="Geostationary transfer orbit">geostationary transfer orbit</a> mission.<sup id="cite_ref-verge_19-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-verge-19">&#91;19&#93;</a></sup> In March 2017, SpaceX became the first to successfully re-launch and land the first stage of an orbital rocket.<sup id="cite_ref-bbc2017reusecore_20-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-bbc2017reusecore-20">&#91;20&#93;</a></sup> In January 2020, with the third launch of the <a href="/wiki/SpaceX_Starlink" title="SpaceX Starlink">Starlink</a> project, SpaceX became the largest commercial satellite constellation operator in the world.<sup id="cite_ref-21" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-21">&#91;21&#93;</a></sup>\n<sup id="cite_ref-22" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-22">&#91;22&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>In September 2016, CEO <a href="/wiki/Elon_Musk" title="Elon Musk">Elon Musk</a> unveiled the <a href="/wiki/Interplanetary_Transport_System" class="mw-redirect" title="Interplanetary Transport System">Interplanetary Transport System</a>, a privately funded launch system to develop spaceflight technology for use in crewed <a href="/wiki/Interplanetary_spaceflight" title="Interplanetary spaceflight">interplanetary spaceflight</a>. In 2018, Musk unveiled an updated configuration of the system, named <a href="/wiki/SpaceX_Starship" title="SpaceX Starship">Starship</a>, which is planned to be fully reusable and will be the largest rocket ever on its debut, scheduled for the early 2020s.<sup id="cite_ref-23" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-23">&#91;23&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-24" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-24">&#91;24&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<div id="toc" class="toc"><input type="checkbox" role="button" id="toctogglecheckbox" class="toctogglecheckbox" style="display:none" /><div class="toctext">Kennedy Space Center</span></a></li>\n<li class="toclevel-3 tocsection-21"><a href="#Brownsville"><span class="tocnumber">4.3.4</span> <span class="toctext">Brownsville</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li class="toclevel-2 tocsection-22"><a href="#Satellite_prototyping_facility"><span class="tocnumber">4.4</span> <span class="toctext">Satellite prototyping facility</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li class="toclevel-1 tocsection-23"><a href="#Launch_contracts"><span class="tocnumber">5</span> <span <span class="toctext">International contracts</span></a>\n<ul>\n<li class="toclevel-3 tocsection-31"><a href="#Kazakhstan"><span class="tocnumber">5.3.1</span> <span class="toctext">Kazakhstan</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n<li class="toclevel-1 tocsection-32"><a href="#Launch_market_competition_and_pricing_pressure"><span class="tocnumber">6</span> <span class="toctext">Launch market competition and pricing pressure</span></a></li>\n<li class="toclevel-1 tocsection-33"><a href="#See_also"><span class="tocnumber">7</span> <span class="toctext">See also</span></a></li>\n<li class="toclevel-1 tocsection-34"><a href="#References"><span class="tocnumber">8</span> <span class="toctext">References</span></a></li>\n<li class="toclevel-1 tocsection-35"><a href="#External_links"><span class="tocnumber">9</span> <span class="toctext">External links</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="History">History</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=SpaceX&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1" title="Edit section: History">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>\n<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main article: <a href="/wiki/History_of_SpaceX" title="History of SpaceX">History of SpaceX</a></div>\n<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Dragon_capsule_and_SpaceX_employees_(16491695667).jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/af/Dragon_capsule_and_SpaceX_employees_%2816491695667%29.jpg/220px-Dragon_capsule_and_SpaceX_employees_%2816491695667%29.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="147" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/af/Dragon_capsule_and_SpaceX_employees_%2816491695667%29.jpg/330px-Dragon_capsule_and_SpaceX_employees_%2816491695667%29.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/af/Dragon_capsule_and_SpaceX_employees_%2816491695667%29.jpg/440px-Dragon_capsule_and_SpaceX_employees_%2816491695667%29.jpg 2x" data-file-width="3000" data-file-height="2000" /></a>  <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Dragon_capsule_and_SpaceX_employees_(16491695667).jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>SpaceX employees with the Dragon capsule at SpaceX HQ in Hawthorne, California, February 2015</div></div></div>\n<p>In 2001, <a href="/wiki/Elon_Musk" title="Elon Musk">Elon Musk</a> conceptualized <i>Mars Oasis</i>, a project to land a miniature experimental greenhouse and grow <a href="/wiki/Plant" title="Plant">plants</a> on Mars. "This would be the furthest that life\xe2\x80\x99s ever traveled"<sup id="cite_ref-25" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-25">&#91;25&#93;</a></sup> in an attempt to regain public interest in space exploration and increase the <a href="/wiki/Budget_of_NASA" title="Budget of NASA">budget of NASA</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-26" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-26">&#91;26&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-spectrum_27-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-spectrum-27">&#91;27&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-youtube.com_28-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-youtube.com-28">&#91;28&#93;</a></sup> Musk tried to buy cheap rockets from Russia but returned empty-handed after failing to find rockets for an affordable price.<sup id="cite_ref-A&amp;Ssmithsonian201201_29-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-A&amp;Ssmithsonian201201-29">&#91;29&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-:0_30-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:0-30">&#91;30&#93;</a></sup>\nOn the flight home, Musk realized that he could start a company that could build the affordable rockets he needed.<sup id="cite_ref-:0_30-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:0-30">&#91;30&#93;</a></sup> According to early <a href="/wiki/Tesla,_Inc." title="Tesla, Inc.">Tesla</a> and SpaceX investor <a href="/wiki/Steve_Jurvetson" title="Steve Jurvetson">Steve Jurvetson</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-31" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-31">&#91;31&#93;</a></sup> Musk calculated that the raw materials for building a rocket actually were only three percent of the sales price of a rocket at the time. By applying <a href="/wiki/Vertical_integration" title="Vertical integration">vertical integration</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-A&amp;Ssmithsonian201201_29-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-A&amp;Ssmithsonian201201-29">&#91;29&#93;</a></sup> producing around 85% of launch hardware in-house,<sup id="cite_ref-32" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-32">&#91;32&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-33" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-33">&#91;33&#93;</a></sup> and the modular approach from software engineering, SpaceX could cut launch price by a factor of ten and still enjoy a 70% <a href="/wiki/Gross_margin" title="Gross margin">gross margin</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-34" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-34">&#91;34&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Launch_of_Falcon_9_carrying_ORBCOMM_OG2-M1_(16601442698).jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1d/Launch_of_Falcon_9_carrying_ORBCOMM_OG2-M1_%2816601442698%29.jpg/220px-Launch_of_Falcon_9_carrying_ORBCOMM_OG2-M1_%2816601442698%29.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="330" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1d/Launch_of_Falcon_9_carrying_ORBCOMM_OG2-M1_%2816601442698%29.jpg/330px-Launch_of_Falcon_9_carrying_ORBCOMM_OG2-M1_%2816601442698%29.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1d/Launch_of_Falcon_9_carrying_ORBCOMM_OG2-M1_%2816601442698%29.jpg/440px-Launch_of_Falcon_9_carrying_ORBCOMM_OG2-M1_%2816601442698%29.jpg 2x" data-file-width="2000" data-file-height="3000" /></a>  <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Launch_of_Falcon_9_carrying_ORBCOMM_OG2-M1_(16601442698).jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>Launch of Falcon 9 carrying ORBCOMM OG2-M1</div></div></div>\n<p>In early 2002, Musk was seeking staff for his new space company, soon to be named SpaceX. Musk approached rocket engineer <a href="/wiki/Tom_Mueller" title="Tom Mueller">Tom Mueller</a> (later SpaceX\'s CTO of Propulsion) and Mueller agreed to work for Musk, and thus SpaceX was born.<sup id="cite_ref-35" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-35">&#91;35&#93;</a></sup> SpaceX was first headquartered in a warehouse in <a href="/wiki/El_Segundo,_California" title="El Segundo, California">El Segundo, California</a>. The company grew rapidly, from 160 employees in November 2005 to 1,100 in 2010,<sup id="cite_ref-36" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-36">&#91;36&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-MU_37-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-MU-37">&#91;37&#93;</a></sup> 3,800 employees and contractors by October 2013,<sup id="cite_ref-pa20131016_38-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-pa20131016-38">&#91;38&#93;</a></sup> nearly 5,000 by late 2015,<sup id="cite_ref-st20151107_39-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-st20151107-39">&#91;39&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-shotwell20160203_40-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-shotwell20160203-40">&#91;40&#93;</a></sup> and about 6,000 in April 2017.<sup id="cite_ref-sir20170414_41-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-sir20170414-41">&#91;41&#93;</a></sup> \nAs of November&#160;2017<sup class="plainlinks noexcerpt noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;"><a class="external text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=SpaceX&amp;action=edit">&#91;update&#93;</a></sup>, the company had grown to nearly 7,000.<sup id="cite_ref-foust20171116_42-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-foust20171116-42">&#91;42&#93;</a></sup>\nIn 2016, Musk gave a speech at the <a href="/wiki/International_Astronautical_Congress" title="International Astronautical Congress">International Astronautical Congress</a>, where he explained that the US government regulates rocket technology as an "advanced weapon technology", making it difficult to hire non-Americans.<sup id="cite_ref-43" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-43">&#91;43&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Falcon_9_Flight_20_OG2_first_stage_post-landing_(23273082823)_cropped.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/19/Falcon_9_Flight_20_OG2_first_stage_post-landing_%2823273082823%29_cropped.jpg/220px-Falcon_9_Flight_20_OG2_first_stage_post-landing_%2823273082823%29_cropped.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="293" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/19/Falcon_9_Flight_20_OG2_first_stage_post-landing_%2823273082823%29_cropped.jpg/330px-Falcon_9_Flight_20_OG2_first_stage_post-landing_%2823273082823%29_cropped.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/19/Falcon_9_Flight_20_OG2_first_stage_post-landing_%2823273082823%29_cropped.jpg/440px-Falcon_9_Flight_20_OG2_first_stage_post-landing_%2823273082823%29_cropped.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1104" data-file-height="1472" /></a>  <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Falcon_9_Flight_20_OG2_first_stage_post-landing_(23273082823)_cropped.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>Falcon 9 rocket\'s first stage on the landing pad after the second successful vertical landing of an orbital rocket stage, OG2 Mission.</div></div></div>\n<p>As of March 2018, SpaceX had over 100 launches on its manifest representing about $12 billion in contract revenue.<sup id="cite_ref-44" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-44">&#91;44&#93;</a></sup> The contracts included both commercial and <a href="/wiki/Federal_government_of_the_United_States" title="Federal government of the United States">government</a> (NASA/DOD) customers.<sup id="cite_ref-about_45-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-about-45">&#91;45&#93;</a></sup> In late 2013, space industry media quoted Musk\'s comments on SpaceX "<a href="/wiki/Competition_(economics)" title="Competition (economics)">forcing\xe2\x80\xa6 increased competitiveness in the launch industry</a>," its major competitors in the commercial <a href="/wiki/Communications_satellite" title="Communications satellite">comsat</a> launch market being <a href="/wiki/Arianespace" title="Arianespace">Arianespace</a>, <a href="/wiki/United_Launch_Alliance" title="United Launch Alliance">United Launch Alliance</a>, and <a href="/wiki/International_Launch_Services" title="International Launch Services">International Launch Services</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-sfn-20131124_46-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-sfn-20131124-46">&#91;46&#93;</a></sup> At the same time, Musk also said that the increased competition would "be a good thing for the future of space." Currently, SpaceX is the leading global commercial launch provider measured by manifested launches.<sup id="cite_ref-:3_47-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:3-47">&#91;47&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:CRS-8_(26239020092).jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/54/CRS-8_%2826239020092%29.jpg/220px-CRS-8_%2826239020092%29.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="147" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/54/CRS-8_%2826239020092%29.jpg/330px-CRS-8_%2826239020092%29.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/54/CRS-8_%2826239020092%29.jpg/440px-CRS-8_%2826239020092%29.jpg 2x" data-file-width="3000" data-file-height="2000" /></a>  <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:CRS-8_(26239020092).jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>Falcon 9 first stage on an ASDS barge after the first successful landing at sea, CRS-8 Mission.</div></div></div>\n<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Goals">Goals</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=SpaceX&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2" title="Edit section: Goals">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>\n<p>Musk has stated that one of his goals is to decrease the cost and improve the reliability of access to <a href="/wiki/Outer_space" title="Outer space">space</a>, ultimately by a factor of ten.<sup id="cite_ref-48" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-48">&#91;48&#93;</a></sup> CEO <a href="/wiki/Elon_Musk" title="Elon Musk">Elon Musk</a> said: "I believe $500 per pound ($1,100/kg) or less is very achievable."<sup id="cite_ref-49" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-49">&#91;49&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Falcon_Heavy_cropped.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2b/Falcon_Heavy_cropped.jpg/220px-Falcon_Heavy_cropped.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="350" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2b/Falcon_Heavy_cropped.jpg/330px-Falcon_Heavy_cropped.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2b/Falcon_Heavy_cropped.jpg/440px-Falcon_Heavy_cropped.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1077" data-file-height="1715" /></a>  <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Falcon_Heavy_cropped.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>Falcon Heavy Rocket on <a href="/wiki/Kennedy_Space_Center_Launch_Complex_39" title="Kennedy Space Center Launch Complex 39">Launch Pad 39A</a> in <a href="/wiki/Cape_Canaveral,_Florida" title="Cape Canaveral, Florida">Cape Canaveral, Florida</a>.</div></div></div>\n<p>A major goal of SpaceX has been to develop a <a href="/wiki/SpaceX_reusable_launch_system_development_program" title="SpaceX reusable launch system development program">rapidly reusable launch system</a>. As of March&#160;2013<sup class="plainlinks noexcerpt noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;"><a class="external text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=SpaceX&amp;action=edit">&#91;update&#93;</a></sup>, the publicly announced aspects of this technology development effort include an active test campaign of the low-altitude, low-speed <a href="/wiki/Grasshopper_(rocket)" title="Grasshopper (rocket)">Grasshopper</a> <a href="/wiki/VTVL" title="VTVL">vertical takeoff, vertical landing</a> (VTVL) technology demonstrator rocket,<sup id="cite_ref-satspot20110926_50-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-satspot20110926-50">&#91;50&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-sfn20120709_51-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-sfn20120709-51">&#91;51&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-msnbc20110927_52-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-msnbc20110927-52">&#91;52&#93;</a></sup> and a high-altitude, high-speed <a href="/wiki/Falcon_9" title="Falcon 9">Falcon 9</a> post-mission booster return test campaign. In 2015, SpaceX successfully landed the first orbital rocket stage on December 21.\n</p><p>In 2017, SpaceX formed a <a href="/wiki/Subsidiary" title="Subsidiary">subsidiary</a>, <a href="/wiki/The_Boring_Company" title="The Boring Company">The Boring Company</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-hawthore20180911_53-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-hawthore20180911-53">&#91;53&#93;</a></sup> and began work to construct a short test tunnel on and adjacent to the SpaceX headquarters and manufacturing facility, utilizing a small number of SpaceX employees,<sup id="cite_ref-lat20171121_54-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-lat20171121-54">&#91;54&#93;</a></sup> which was completed in May 2018,<sup id="cite_ref-bi20180511_55-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-bi20180511-55">&#91;55&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-56" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-56">&#91;56&#93;</a></sup> and opened to the public in December 2018.<sup id="cite_ref-wsj20181217_57-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-wsj20181217-57">&#91;57&#93;</a></sup>\nDuring 2018, The Boring Company was <a href="/wiki/Spin-out" class="mw-redirect" title="Spin-out">spun out</a> into a separate <a href="/wiki/Corporate_entity" class="mw-redirect" title="Corporate entity">corporate entity</a> with 6% of the equity going to SpaceX, less than 10% to early employees, and the remainder of the equity to Elon Musk.<sup id="cite_ref-wsj20181217_57-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-wsj20181217-57">&#91;57&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>At the 2016 International Astronautical Congress, Musk announced his plans to build large spaceships to reach Mars.<sup id="cite_ref-58" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-58">&#91;58&#93;</a></sup> Using the Starship, Musk plans to land at least two uncrewed cargo ships to Mars in 2022. The first missions will be used to seek out sources of water and build a propellant plant. In 2024, Musk plans to fly four additional ships to Mars including the first people. From there, additional missions would work to establish a Mars colony.<sup id="cite_ref-:6_8-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:6-8">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-59" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-59">&#91;59&#93;</a></sup> Musk\'s advocacy for the long-term settlement of Mars, goes far beyond what SpaceX projects to build;<sup id="cite_ref-dn20121213_60-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-dn20121213-60">&#91;60&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-61" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-61">&#91;61&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-pa20140205_62-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-pa20140205-62">&#91;62&#93;</a></sup> a successful colonization would ultimately involve many more economic actors\xe2\x80\x94whether individuals, companies, or governments\xe2\x80\x94to facilitate the growth of the human presence on Mars over many decades.<sup id="cite_ref-ars20160928_63-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ars20160928-63">&#91;63&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-sn20161010_64-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-sn20161010-64">&#91;64&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-gw-20160927_65-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-gw-20160927-65">&#91;65&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Achievements">Achievements</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=SpaceX&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3" title="Edit section: Achievements">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>\n<p>Major achievements of SpaceX are in the reuse of orbital class launch vehicles and cost reduction in the spacelaunch industry. Most notable of these being the continued landings and relaunches of the first stage of Falcon 9. As of November 2019, SpaceX has used a single first stage booster, <a href="/wiki/Falcon_9_booster_B1048" title="Falcon 9 booster B1048">B1048</a>, at most four times.\nSpaceX is defined as a private space company and thus its achievements can also be counted as firsts by a private company. \n</p><p>Landmark achievements of SpaceX in chronological order include:<sup id="cite_ref-66" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-66">&#91;66&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<ul><li>The first privately funded liquid-fueled rocket to reach orbit (<a href="/wiki/Falcon_1#Fourth_flight" title="Falcon 1">Falcon 1 flight 4</a> on 28 September 2008)</li>\n<li>The first privately developed liquid-fueled rocket to put a commercial satellite in orbit (<a href="/wiki/RazakSAT" title="RazakSAT">RazakSAT</a> on Falcon 1 flight 5 on 14 July 2009)</li>\n<li>The first private company to successfully launch, orbit, and recover a spacecraft (<a href="/wiki/SpaceX_Dragon" title="SpaceX Dragon">SpaceX Dragon</a> on <a href="/wiki/SpaceX_COTS_Demo_Flight_1" title="SpaceX COTS Demo Flight 1">COTS Demo Flight 1</a> on 9 December 2010)</li>\n<li>The first private company to send a spacecraft to the International Space Station (<a href="/wiki/Dragon_C2%2B" title="Dragon C2+">Dragon C2+</a> on 25 May 2012)</li>\n<li>The first private company to send a satellite into geosynchronous orbit (<a href="/wiki/SES-8" title="SES-8">SES-8</a> on Falcon 9 flight 7 on 3 December 2013)</li>\n<li>The first landing of an orbital rocket\'s first stage on land (<a href="/wiki/Falcon_9_flight_20" title="Falcon 9 flight 20">Falcon 9 flight 20</a> on 22 December 2015)</li>\n<li>The first landing of an orbital rocket\'s first stage on an ocean platform (<a href="/wiki/Falcon_9_flight_23" class="mw-redirect" title="Falcon 9 flight 23">Falcon 9 flight 23</a> on 8 April 2016)</li>\n<li>The first relaunch and landing of a used orbital rocket stage (<a href="/wiki/B1021" class="mw-redirect" title="B1021">B1021</a> on <a href="/wiki/Falcon_9_flight_32" class="mw-redirect" title="Falcon 9 flight 32">Falcon 9 flight 32</a> on 30 March 2017)<sup id="cite_ref-:2_67-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:2-67">&#91;67&#93;</a></sup></li>\n<li>The first controlled flyback and recovery of a payload fairing (Falcon 9 flight 32 on 30 March 2017)<sup id="cite_ref-fairingrec_68-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-fairingrec-68">&#91;68&#93;</a></sup></li>\n<li>The first reflight of a commercial cargo spacecraft. (<a href="/wiki/Dragon_C106" class="mw-redirect" title="Dragon C106">Dragon C106</a> on <a href="/wiki/CRS-11" class="mw-redirect" title="CRS-11">CRS-11</a> mission on 3 June 2017)<sup id="cite_ref-69" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-69">&#91;69&#93;</a></sup></li>\n<li>The first private company to send a human-rated spacecraft to space (<a href="/wiki/Crew_Dragon_Demo-1" title="Crew Dragon Demo-1">Crew Dragon Demo-1, on Falcon 9 flight 69</a> on 2 March 2019)</li>\n<li>The first private company to autonomously dock a spacecraft to the International Space Station (<a href="/wiki/Crew_Dragon_Demo-1" title="Crew Dragon Demo-1">Crew Dragon Demo-1, on Falcon 9 flight 69</a> on 2 March 2019)</li>\n<li>The first use of a full flow staged combustion cycle engine (<a href="/wiki/Raptor_(rocket_engine_family)" class="mw-redirect" title="Raptor (rocket engine family)">Raptor</a>) in a free flying vehicle (<a href="/wiki/Starhopper" class="mw-redirect" title="Starhopper">Starhopper</a>, multiple tests in 2019).</li>\n<li>The first reuse of payload fairing. On 11 November 2019 on <a href="/wiki/Starlink_L1" class="mw-redirect" title="Starlink L1">Starlink L1</a> Falcon 9 launch. Fairing was from the <a href="/wiki/ArabSat-6A" class="mw-redirect" title="ArabSat-6A">ArabSat-6A</a> mission in April earlier that year.</li></ul>\n<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Setbacks">Setbacks</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=SpaceX&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4" title="Edit section: Setbacks">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>\n<p>In March 2013, a <a href="/wiki/SpaceX_Dragon" title="SpaceX Dragon">Dragon spacecraft</a> in <a href="/wiki/Orbit" title="Orbit">orbit</a> developed issues with its thrusters that limited its control capabilities. SpaceX engineers were able to remotely clear the blockages within a short period, and the spacecraft was able to successfully complete its mission to and from the <a href="/wiki/International_Space_Station" title="International Space Station">International Space Station</a>.\n</p><p>In late June 2015, <a href="/wiki/SpaceX_CRS-7" title="SpaceX CRS-7">CRS-7</a> launched a <a href="/wiki/SpaceX_Dragon" title="SpaceX Dragon">Cargo Dragon</a> atop a <a href="/wiki/Falcon_9" title="Falcon 9">Falcon 9</a> to resupply the <a href="/wiki/International_Space_Station" title="International Space Station">International Space Station</a>. All <a href="/wiki/Telemetry" title="Telemetry">telemetry</a> readings were nominal until 2 minutes and 19 seconds into the flight, when a loss of helium pressure was detected and a cloud of vapor appeared outside the second stage. A few seconds after this, the second stage exploded. The first stage continued to fly for a few seconds before disintegrating due to <a href="/wiki/Dynamic_pressure" title="Dynamic pressure">aerodynamic forces</a>. The capsule was thrown off and survived the explosion, transmitting data until it was destroyed on impact.<sup id="cite_ref-Stephen_Clark_for_spaceflightnow.com_70-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Stephen_Clark_for_spaceflightnow.com-70">&#91;70&#93;</a></sup> Later it was revealed that the capsule could have landed intact if it had <a href="/wiki/Software" title="Software">software</a> to deploy its parachutes in case of a launch mishap.<sup id="cite_ref-71" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-71">&#91;71&#93;</a></sup> The problem was discovered to be a failed 2-foot-long steel strut purchased from a supplier<sup id="cite_ref-72" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-72">&#91;72&#93;</a></sup> to hold a <a href="/wiki/Helium" title="Helium">helium</a> <a href="/wiki/Pressure_vessel" title="Pressure vessel">pressure vessel</a> that broke free due to the force of <a href="/wiki/Acceleration" title="Acceleration">acceleration</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-73" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-73">&#91;73&#93;</a></sup> This caused a breach and allowed high-pressure helium to escape into the low-pressure propellant tank, causing the failure. The <a href="/wiki/SpaceX_Dragon" title="SpaceX Dragon">Dragon</a> software issue was also fixed in addition to an analysis of the entire program in order to ensure proper abort mechanisms are in place for future rockets and their payload.<sup id="cite_ref-74" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-74">&#91;74&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>In early September 2016, a Falcon 9 exploded during a propellant fill operation for a standard pre-launch <a href="/wiki/Wet_dress_rehearsal" class="mw-redirect" title="Wet dress rehearsal">static fire test</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-75" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-75">&#91;75&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-76" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-76">&#91;76&#93;</a></sup> The payload, the <a href="/wiki/Spacecom" title="Spacecom">Spacecom</a> <a href="/wiki/Amos-6" title="Amos-6">Amos-6</a> communications satellite valued at $200 million, was destroyed.<sup id="cite_ref-77" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-77">&#91;77&#93;</a></sup> Musk described the event as the "most difficult and complex failure" in SpaceX\'s history; SpaceX reviewed nearly 3,000 channels of telemetry and video data covering a period of 35\xe2\x80\x9355 milliseconds for the postmortem.<sup id="cite_ref-78" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-78">&#91;78&#93;</a></sup> Musk reported that the explosion was caused by the liquid oxygen that is used as propellant turning so cold that it solidified and ignited with <a href="/wiki/Composite_overwrapped_pressure_vessel" title="Composite overwrapped pressure vessel">carbon composite</a> helium vessels.<sup id="cite_ref-verge-sept-explod-cause_79-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-verge-sept-explod-cause-79">&#91;79&#93;</a></sup> Though not considered an unsuccessful flight, the rocket explosion sent the company into a four-month launch hiatus while it worked out what went wrong. SpaceX returned to flight in January 2017.<sup id="cite_ref-plarson_80-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-plarson-80">&#91;80&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>On 28 June 2019, SpaceX announced that it had lost contact with three of the 60 <a href="/wiki/Satellite" title="Satellite">satellites</a> making up the Starlink <a href="/wiki/Satellite_internet_constellation" title="Satellite internet constellation">megaconstellation</a>. The dysfunctional satellites\' orbits are expected to slowly decay until they disintegrate in the <a href="/wiki/Atmosphere" title="Atmosphere">atmosphere</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-81" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-81">&#91;81&#93;</a></sup> However, the rate of failure for satellites in megaconstellations consisting of thousands of satellites has raised concerns that these <a href="/wiki/Constellation" title="Constellation">constellations</a> could litter the <a href="/wiki/Low_Earth_orbit" title="Low Earth orbit">Earth\'s lower orbit</a>, with serious detrimental consequences for future <a href="/wiki/Spaceflight" title="Spaceflight">space flights</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-82" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-82">&#91;82&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h3><span id="Ownership.2C_funding_and_valuation"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="Ownership,_funding_and_valuation">Ownership, funding and valuation</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=SpaceX&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5" title="Edit section: Ownership, funding and valuation">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>\n<p>In August 2008, SpaceX accepted a $20 million investment from <a href="/wiki/Founders_Fund" title="Founders Fund">Founders Fund</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-83" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-83">&#91;83&#93;</a></sup> In early 2012, approximately two-thirds of the company were owned by its founder<sup id="cite_ref-84" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-84">&#91;84&#93;</a></sup> and his 70 million shares were then estimated to be worth $875 million on <a href="/wiki/Private_equity" title="Private equity">private markets</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-IPO_85-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-IPO-85">&#91;85&#93;</a></sup> which roughly valued SpaceX at $1.3 billion as of February 2012.<sup id="cite_ref-cnbc20120427_86-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-cnbc20120427-86">&#91;86&#93;</a></sup> After the <a href="/wiki/Dragon_C2%2B" title="Dragon C2+">COTS 2+</a> flight in May 2012, the company private equity valuation nearly doubled to $2.4 billion.<sup id="cite_ref-87" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-87">&#91;87&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-88" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-88">&#91;88&#93;</a></sup> In January 2015, SpaceX raised $1 billion in funding from <a href="/wiki/Google" title="Google">Google</a> and <a href="/wiki/Fidelity_Ventures" title="Fidelity Ventures">Fidelity</a>, in exchange for 8.333% of the company, establishing the company valuation at approximately $12 billion. Google and Fidelity joined prior investors <a href="/wiki/Draper_Fisher_Jurvetson" title="Draper Fisher Jurvetson">Draper Fisher Jurvetson</a>, <a href="/wiki/Founders_Fund" title="Founders Fund">Founders Fund</a>, Valor Equity Partners and <a href="/wiki/Capricorn_Investment_Holdings" class="mw-redirect" title="Capricorn Investment Holdings">Capricorn</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-89" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-89">&#91;89&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-90" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-90">&#91;90&#93;</a></sup> In July 2017, the Company raised US$350m at a valuation of US$21 billion.<sup id="cite_ref-91" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-91">&#91;91&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>As of May&#160;2012<sup class="plainlinks noexcerpt noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;"><a class="external text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=SpaceX&amp;action=edit">&#91;update&#93;</a></sup>, SpaceX had operated on total funding of approximately $1 billion in its first ten years of operation. Of this, private equity provided about $200M, with Musk investing approximately $100M and other investors having put in about $100M (<a href="/wiki/Founders_Fund" title="Founders Fund">Founders Fund</a>, <a href="/wiki/Draper_Fisher_Jurvetson" title="Draper Fisher Jurvetson">Draper Fisher Jurvetson</a>, etc.).<sup id="cite_ref-92" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-92">&#91;92&#93;</a></sup> The remainder has come from progress payments on long-term launch contracts and development contracts. By March 2018, SpaceX had contracts for 100 launch missions, and each of those contracts provide down payments at contract signing, plus many are paying progress payments as launch vehicle components are built in advance of mission launch, driven in part by US accounting rules for <a href="/wiki/Revenue_recognition#Long-term_contracts" title="Revenue recognition">recognizing long-term revenue</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-about_45-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-about-45">&#91;45&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<div class="thumb tright" style=""><div class="thumbinner" style="width:fit-content; width:-moz-fit-content; width:-webkit-fit-content;"><div class="thumbimage noresize" style="width:auto;"><style data-mw-deduplicate="TemplateStyles:r888230452">@media all and (max-width:720px){body.skin-minerva .mw-parser-output div.mw-graph{min-width:auto!important;max-width:100%;overflow-x:auto;overflow-y:visible}}.mw-parser-output .mw-graph-img{width:inherit;height:inherit}</style><div class="mw-graph" style="min-width:250px;min-height:150px"><img class="mw-graph-img" src="/api/rest_v1/page/graph/png/SpaceX/0/227cea997cf9e7b20c5ba5d159d885539c55f5e6.png" /></div></div><div class="thumbcaption">Successful SpaceX launches by year<sup id="cite_ref-93" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-93">&#91;93&#93;</a></sup></div></div></div>\n<p>Congressional testimony by SpaceX in 2017 suggested that the NASA <a href="/wiki/Space_Act_Agreement" title="Space Act Agreement">Space Act Agreement</a> process of "setting only a <a href="/wiki/Requirement#Types_of_requirement" title="Requirement">high-level requirement</a> for cargo transport to the space station [while] leaving the details to industry" had allowed SpaceX to design and develop the Falcon 9 rocket on its own at substantially lower cost. "According to <a href="/wiki/NASA" title="NASA">NASA\'s</a> own independently verified numbers, SpaceX\xe2\x80\x99s development costs of both the Falcon 1 and Falcon 9 rockets were estimated at approximately <span style="white-space: nowrap">US$390 million</span> in total. "In 2011, NASA estimated that it would have cost the agency about <span style="white-space: nowrap">US$4 billion</span> to develop a rocket like the Falcon 9 booster based upon NASA\'s traditional contracting processes". The Falcon 9 launch system, with an estimated improvement at least four to ten times over traditional cost-plus contracting estimates, about $400 million vs. $4 billion in savings through the usage of Space Act Agreements.<sup id="cite_ref-:5_94-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:5-94">&#91;94&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>In April 2019, the Wall Street Journal reported that SpaceX was raising another $500 million in funding.<sup id="cite_ref-95" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-95">&#91;95&#93;</a></sup> In May 2019, <a href="/wiki/Space_News" class="mw-redirect" title="Space News">Space News</a> reported SpaceX "raised $1.022 billion" the day after SpaceX launched 60 satellites towards their 12,000 satellite plan named <i>Starlink broadband constellation</i>.<sup id="cite_ref-96" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-96">&#91;96&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-97" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-97">&#91;97&#93;</a></sup> As of May 31, 2019, the value of SpaceX has risen to $33.3 billion.<sup id="cite_ref-98" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-98">&#91;98&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>In June 2019, SpaceX started to raise $300 million of investment, mostly from the <a href="/wiki/Ontario_Teachers%27_Pension_Plan" title="Ontario Teachers&#39; Pension Plan">Ontario Teachers\' Pension Plan</a>, which has $191.1 billion in assets under management.<sup id="cite_ref-99" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-99">&#91;99&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Hardware">Hardware</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=SpaceX&amp;action=edit&amp;section=6" title="Edit section: Hardware">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>\n<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Launch_vehicles">Launch vehicles</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=SpaceX&amp;action=edit&amp;section=7" title="Edit section: Launch vehicles">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>\n<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main article: <a href="/wiki/SpaceX_launch_vehicles" title="SpaceX launch vehicles">SpaceX launch vehicles</a></div>\n<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:CRS-18_Mission_(48380511427).jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/83/CRS-18_Mission_%2848380511427%29.jpg/220px-CRS-18_Mission_%2848380511427%29.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="147" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/83/CRS-18_Mission_%2848380511427%29.jpg/330px-CRS-18_Mission_%2848380511427%29.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/83/CRS-18_Mission_%2848380511427%29.jpg/440px-CRS-18_Mission_%2848380511427%29.jpg 2x" data-file-width="3000" data-file-height="2000" /></a>  <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:CRS-18_Mission_(48380511427).jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>The landing of a <a href="/wiki/Falcon_9_Block_5" title="Falcon 9 Block 5">Falcon 9 Block 5</a> first stage at Cape Canaveral in July 2019 \xe2\x80\x93 <a href="/wiki/VTVL" title="VTVL">VTVL</a> technologies are utilized in many of SpaceX\'s launch vehicles</div></div></div>\n<p><a href="/wiki/Falcon_1" title="Falcon 1">Falcon 1</a> was a small rocket capable of placing several hundred kilograms into low Earth orbit.<sup id="cite_ref-Falcon9_overview_100-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Falcon9_overview-100">&#91;100&#93;</a></sup>  It functioned as an early test-bed for developing concepts and components for the larger Falcon 9.<sup id="cite_ref-Falcon9_overview_100-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Falcon9_overview-100">&#91;100&#93;</a></sup> Falcon 1 attempted five flights between 2006 and 2009. With Falcon I, when Musk announced his plans for it before a subcommittee in the Senate in 2004, he discussed that Falcon I would be the \'worlds only semi-reusable orbital rocket\' apart from the space shuttle.<sup id="cite_ref-101" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-101">&#91;101&#93;</a></sup> On September 28, 2008, on its fourth attempt, the Falcon 1 successfully reached orbit, becoming the first privately funded, liquid-fueled rocket to do so.<sup id="cite_ref-102" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-102">&#91;102&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p><a href="/wiki/Falcon_9" title="Falcon 9">Falcon 9</a> is an <a href="/wiki/Evolved_Expendable_Launch_Vehicle" class="mw-redirect" title="Evolved Expendable Launch Vehicle">EELV</a>-class <a href="/wiki/Comparison_of_medium_lift_launch_systems" class="mw-redirect" title="Comparison of medium lift launch systems">medium-lift</a> vehicle capable of delivering up to 22,800 kilograms (50,265&#160;lb) to orbit, and is intended to compete with the <a href="/wiki/Delta_IV_rocket" class="mw-redirect" title="Delta IV rocket">Delta IV</a> and the <a href="/wiki/Atlas_V_rocket" class="mw-redirect" title="Atlas V rocket">Atlas V</a> rockets, as well as other launch providers around the world. It has nine <a href="/wiki/Merlin_(rocket_engine)" class="mw-redirect" title="Merlin (rocket engine)">Merlin</a> engines in its first stage.<sup id="cite_ref-SpaceX_Press_2005-09-08_103-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-SpaceX_Press_2005-09-08-103">&#91;103&#93;</a></sup> The <a href="/wiki/Falcon_9_v1.0" title="Falcon 9 v1.0">Falcon 9 v1.0</a> rocket successfully reached orbit on its first attempt on June 4, 2010. Its third flight, <a href="/wiki/COTS_Demo_Flight_2" class="mw-redirect" title="COTS Demo Flight 2">COTS Demo Flight 2</a>, launched on May 22, 2012, and was the first <a href="/wiki/Private_spaceflight" title="Private spaceflight">commercial</a> spacecraft to reach and dock with the International Space Station.<sup id="cite_ref-cbcnews_104-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-cbcnews-104">&#91;104&#93;</a></sup> The vehicle was upgraded to <a href="/wiki/Falcon_9_v1.1" title="Falcon 9 v1.1">Falcon 9 v1.1</a> in 2013 and again in 2015 to the current <a href="/wiki/Falcon_9_Full_Thrust" title="Falcon 9 Full Thrust">Falcon 9 Full Thrust</a> version. As of February&#160;2018<sup class="plainlinks noexcerpt noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;"><a class="external text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=SpaceX&amp;action=edit">&#91;update&#93;</a></sup>, Falcon 9 vehicles have flown <a href="/wiki/List_of_Falcon_9_and_Falcon_Heavy_launches" title="List of Falcon 9 and Falcon Heavy launches">49 successful missions</a> with one failure, the CRS-7 mission. An additional vehicle was destroyed during a routine test several days prior to a scheduled launch in 2016.\n</p><p>In 2011, SpaceX began development of the <a href="/wiki/Falcon_Heavy" title="Falcon Heavy">Falcon Heavy</a>, a <a href="/wiki/Comparison_of_heavy_lift_launch_systems" class="mw-redirect" title="Comparison of heavy lift launch systems">heavy-lift</a> rocket configured using a cluster of three Falcon 9 first stage <a href="/wiki/Modular_rocket" title="Modular rocket">cores</a> with a total 27 <a href="/wiki/Merlin_1D" class="mw-redirect" title="Merlin 1D">Merlin 1D</a> engines and <a href="/wiki/Propellant_crossfeed" class="mw-redirect" title="Propellant crossfeed">propellant crossfeed</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-sxfh2011_105-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-sxfh2011-105">&#91;105&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-nsw20130103_106-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsw20130103-106">&#91;106&#93;</a></sup> The Falcon Heavy successfully flew on its inaugural mission on February 6, 2018 with a payload consisting of Musk\'s personal <a href="/wiki/Tesla_Roadster_(2008)" title="Tesla Roadster (2008)">Tesla Roadster</a> into <a href="/wiki/Heliocentric_orbit" title="Heliocentric orbit">heliocentric orbit</a><sup id="cite_ref-107" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-107">&#91;107&#93;</a></sup> The first stage would be capable of lifting 63,800 kilograms (140,660&#160;lb) to <a href="/wiki/Low_Earth_orbit" title="Low Earth orbit">LEO</a> with the 27 Merlin 1D engines producing 22,819 <a href="/wiki/Newton_(unit)" title="Newton (unit)">kN</a> of thrust at sea level, and 24,681&#160;kN in space. At the time of its first launch, SpaceX described their Falcon Heavy as "the world\'s most powerful rocket in operation".<sup id="cite_ref-108" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-108">&#91;108&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Rocket_engines">Rocket engines</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=SpaceX&amp;action=edit&amp;section=8" title="Edit section: Rocket engines">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>\n<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main article: <a href="/wiki/SpaceX_rocket_engines" title="SpaceX rocket engines">SpaceX rocket engines</a></div>\n<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:SpaceX_Testing_Merlin_1D_Engine_In_Texas.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/44/SpaceX_Testing_Merlin_1D_Engine_In_Texas.jpg/220px-SpaceX_Testing_Merlin_1D_Engine_In_Texas.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="147" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/44/SpaceX_Testing_Merlin_1D_Engine_In_Texas.jpg/330px-SpaceX_Testing_Merlin_1D_Engine_In_Texas.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/44/SpaceX_Testing_Merlin_1D_Engine_In_Texas.jpg/440px-SpaceX_Testing_Merlin_1D_Engine_In_Texas.jpg 2x" data-file-width="921" data-file-height="614" /></a>  <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:SpaceX_Testing_Merlin_1D_Engine_In_Texas.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>The <a href="/wiki/Merlin_(rocket_engine_family)#Merlin_1D" class="mw-redirect" title="Merlin (rocket engine family)">Merlin 1D</a> engine, SpaceX\'s most prolific engine, undergoing testing at SpaceX\'s Rocket Development and Test Facility in McGregor, Texas</div></div></div> \n<p>Since the founding of SpaceX in 2002, the company has developed three families of <a href="/wiki/Rocket_engine" title="Rocket engine">rocket engines</a>&#160;\xe2\x80\x94 <a href="/wiki/Merlin_(rocket_engine)" class="mw-redirect" title="Merlin (rocket engine)">Merlin</a> and the retired <a href="/wiki/Kestrel_(rocket_engine)" class="mw-redirect" title="Kestrel (rocket engine)">Kestrel</a> for <a href="/wiki/Launch_vehicle" title="Launch vehicle">launch vehicle</a> propulsion, and the <a href="/wiki/Draco_(rocket_engine_family)" class="mw-redirect" title="Draco (rocket engine family)">Draco</a> control thrusters. SpaceX is currently <a href="/wiki/New_product_development" title="New product development">developing</a> two further rocket engines: <a href="/wiki/SuperDraco_(rocket_engine)" class="mw-redirect" title="SuperDraco (rocket engine)">SuperDraco</a> and <a href="/wiki/Raptor_(rocket_engine_family)" class="mw-redirect" title="Raptor (rocket engine family)">Raptor</a>. SpaceX is currently the world\'s most prolific producer of liquid fuel rocket engines.<sup id="cite_ref-109" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-109">&#91;109&#93;</a></sup> Merlin is a family of rocket engines developed by SpaceX for use on their <a href="/wiki/SpaceX_launch_vehicles" title="SpaceX launch vehicles">launch vehicles</a>. Merlin engines use <a href="/wiki/Liquid_oxygen" title="Liquid oxygen">LOX</a> and <a href="/wiki/RP-1" title="RP-1">RP-1</a> as propellants in a gas-generator power cycle. The Merlin engine was originally designed for sea recovery and reuse. The injector at the heart of Merlin is of the <a href="/wiki/Pintle_injector" title="Pintle injector">pintle</a> type that was first used in the <a href="/wiki/Apollo_Program" class="mw-redirect" title="Apollo Program">Apollo Program</a> for the lunar module landing engine. Propellants are fed via a single shaft, dual impeller <a href="/wiki/Turbo-pump" class="mw-redirect" title="Turbo-pump">turbo-pump</a>. Kestrel is a LOX/RP-1 <a href="/wiki/Pressure-fed_engine_(rocket)" class="mw-redirect" title="Pressure-fed engine (rocket)">pressure-fed</a> rocket engine, and was used as the Falcon 1 rocket\'s second stage main engine. It is built around the same pintle architecture as SpaceX\'s Merlin engine but does not have a <a href="/wiki/Turbo-pump" class="mw-redirect" title="Turbo-pump">turbo-pump</a>, and is fed only by <a href="/wiki/Pressure-fed_engine_(rocket)" class="mw-redirect" title="Pressure-fed engine (rocket)">tank pressure</a>. Its nozzle is <a href="/wiki/Ablation" title="Ablation">ablatively</a> cooled in the chamber and throat, is also <a href="/wiki/Radiative_cooling" title="Radiative cooling">radiatively cooled</a>, and is fabricated from a high strength <a href="/wiki/Niobium" title="Niobium">niobium</a> alloy. Both names for the <a href="/wiki/Merlin_(rocket_engine)" class="mw-redirect" title="Merlin (rocket engine)">Merlin</a> and <a href="/wiki/Kestrel_(rocket_engine)" class="mw-redirect" title="Kestrel (rocket engine)">Kestrel</a> engines are derived from species of North American falcons: the <a href="/wiki/Kestrel" title="Kestrel">kestrel</a> and the <a href="/wiki/Merlin_(bird)" title="Merlin (bird)">merlin</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-110" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-110">&#91;110&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Draco are <a href="/wiki/Hypergolic" class="mw-redirect" title="Hypergolic">hypergolic</a> liquid-propellant rocket engines that utilize <a href="/wiki/Monomethyl_hydrazine" class="mw-redirect" title="Monomethyl hydrazine">monomethyl hydrazine</a> <a href="/wiki/Fuel" title="Fuel">fuel</a> and <a href="/wiki/Nitrogen_tetroxide" class="mw-redirect" title="Nitrogen tetroxide">nitrogen tetroxide</a> <a href="/wiki/Oxidizer" class="mw-redirect" title="Oxidizer">oxidizer</a>. Each Draco thruster generates 400 newtons (90&#160;lbf) of thrust.<sup id="cite_ref-sxu20071210_111-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-sxu20071210-111">&#91;111&#93;</a></sup> They are used as <a href="/wiki/Reaction_control_system" title="Reaction control system">reaction control system</a> (RCS) thrusters on the <a href="/wiki/SpaceX_Dragon" title="SpaceX Dragon">Dragon spacecraft</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-sxF9LVPUG2009_112-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-sxF9LVPUG2009-112">&#91;112&#93;</a></sup> <a href="/wiki/SuperDraco" title="SuperDraco">SuperDraco</a> engines are a much more powerful version of the Draco thrusters, which were initially meant to be used as landing and <a href="/wiki/Launch_escape_system" title="Launch escape system">launch escape system</a> engines on the version 2 Dragon spacecraft, <a href="/wiki/Dragon_2" title="Dragon 2">Dragon 2</a>. The concept of using retro-rockets for landing was scrapped in 2017 when it was decided to perform a traditional parachute descent and <a href="/wiki/Splashdown" title="Splashdown">splashdown</a> at sea.<sup id="cite_ref-113" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-113">&#91;113&#93;</a></sup> <a href="/wiki/Raptor_(rocket_engine_family)" class="mw-redirect" title="Raptor (rocket engine family)">Raptor</a> is a new family of <a href="/wiki/Methane#Liquid_methane_rocket_fuel" title="Methane">methane-fueled</a> <a href="/wiki/Staged_combustion_cycle#Full-flow_staged_combustion_cycle" title="Staged combustion cycle">full flow staged combustion cycle</a> engines to be used in its future Starship launch system.<sup id="cite_ref-114" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-114">&#91;114&#93;</a></sup> Development versions were test fired in late 2016.<sup id="cite_ref-115" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-115">&#91;115&#93;</a></sup> On April 3, 2019, SpaceX conducted a successful static fire test in Texas on its <a href="/wiki/Starship_test_flight_rocket" class="mw-redirect" title="Starship test flight rocket">Starhopper</a> vehicle, which ignited the engine while the vehicle remained tethered to the ground.<sup id="cite_ref-116" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-116">&#91;116&#93;</a></sup> On July 24, 2019 SpaceX conducted a successful test hop of 20 meters of its Starhopper test vehicle.<sup id="cite_ref-117" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-117">&#91;117&#93;</a></sup> On the 28th August 2019 SpaceX\'s Starhopper prototype conducted a successful test hop of 150-meters.<sup id="cite_ref-118" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-118">&#91;118&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Dragon_Spacecraft">Dragon Spacecraft</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=SpaceX&amp;action=edit&amp;section=9" title="Edit section: Dragon Spacecraft">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>\n<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Crew_Dragon_at_the_ISS_for_Demo_Mission_1_(cropped).jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7d/Crew_Dragon_at_the_ISS_for_Demo_Mission_1_%28cropped%29.jpg/220px-Crew_Dragon_at_the_ISS_for_Demo_Mission_1_%28cropped%29.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="165" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7d/Crew_Dragon_at_the_ISS_for_Demo_Mission_1_%28cropped%29.jpg/330px-Crew_Dragon_at_the_ISS_for_Demo_Mission_1_%28cropped%29.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7d/Crew_Dragon_at_the_ISS_for_Demo_Mission_1_%28cropped%29.jpg/440px-Crew_Dragon_at_the_ISS_for_Demo_Mission_1_%28cropped%29.jpg 2x" data-file-width="2000" data-file-height="1500" /></a>  <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Crew_Dragon_at_the_ISS_for_Demo_Mission_1_(cropped).jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>SpaceX\'s <a href="/wiki/Dragon_2" title="Dragon 2">Crew Dragon</a> spacecraft, designed to shuttle crew to and from the International Space Station as part of the <a href="/wiki/Commercial_Crew_Development" title="Commercial Crew Development">Commercial Crew Program</a></div></div></div>\n<p>In 2005, SpaceX announced plans to pursue a human-rated commercial space program through the end of the decade.<sup id="cite_ref-119" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-119">&#91;119&#93;</a></sup> The Dragon is a conventional blunt-cone ballistic capsule which is capable of carrying cargo or up to seven astronauts into orbit and beyond.<sup id="cite_ref-Spaceref_Dragon_first_2006_120-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Spaceref_Dragon_first_2006-120">&#91;120&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Spaceref_Dragon_first_2006_120-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Spaceref_Dragon_first_2006-120">&#91;120&#93;</a></sup> In 2006, NASA announced that the company was one of two selected to provide crew and cargo resupply demonstration contracts to the ISS under the COTS program.<sup id="cite_ref-121" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-121">&#91;121&#93;</a></sup> SpaceX demonstrated cargo resupply and eventually crew transportation services using the Dragon.<sup id="cite_ref-cbcnews_104-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-cbcnews-104">&#91;104&#93;</a></sup> The first flight of a Dragon structural test article took place in June 2010, from Launch Complex 40 at Cape Canaveral Air Force Station during the maiden flight of the <a href="/wiki/Falcon_9" title="Falcon 9">Falcon 9</a> launch vehicle; the <a href="/wiki/Boilerplate_(spaceflight)" title="Boilerplate (spaceflight)">mock-up</a> Dragon lacked avionics, heat shield, and other key elements normally required of a fully operational spacecraft but contained all the necessary characteristics to validate the flight performance of the launch vehicle.<sup id="cite_ref-COTS1presskitSpaceX_122-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-COTS1presskitSpaceX-122">&#91;122&#93;</a></sup> An operational Dragon spacecraft was launched in December 2010 aboard <a href="/wiki/COTS_Demo_Flight_1" class="mw-redirect" title="COTS Demo Flight 1">COTS Demo Flight 1</a>, the Falcon 9\'s second flight, and safely returned to Earth after two orbits, completing all its mission objectives.<sup id="cite_ref-BBCLaunchDec2010_123-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-BBCLaunchDec2010-123">&#91;123&#93;</a></sup> In 2012, Dragon became the first commercial spacecraft to deliver cargo to the International Space Station,<sup id="cite_ref-cbcnews_104-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-cbcnews-104">&#91;104&#93;</a></sup> and has since been conducting regular resupply services to the ISS.<sup id="cite_ref-124" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-124">&#91;124&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>In April 2011, NASA issued a $75 million contract, as part of its second-round <a href="/wiki/CCDev" class="mw-redirect" title="CCDev">commercial crew development</a> (CCDev) program, for SpaceX to develop an integrated launch escape system for Dragon in preparation for human-rating it as a crew transport vehicle to the ISS.<sup id="cite_ref-sdc20110418_125-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-sdc20110418-125">&#91;125&#93;</a></sup> In August 2012, NASA awarded SpaceX a firm, fixed-price <a href="/wiki/Space_Act_Agreement" title="Space Act Agreement">SAA</a> with the objective of producing a detailed design of the entire crew transportation system. This contract includes numerous key technical and certification milestones, an uncrewed flight test, a crewed flight test, and six operational missions following system certification.<sup id="cite_ref-:4_126-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:4-126">&#91;126&#93;</a></sup> The fully autonomous Crew Dragon spacecraft is expected to be one of the safest crewed spacecraft systems. Reusable in nature, the Crew Dragon will offer savings to NASA.<sup id="cite_ref-:4_126-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:4-126">&#91;126&#93;</a></sup> SpaceX conducted a test of an empty Crew Dragon to ISS in early 2019, and later in the year they plan to launch a crewed Dragon which will send US astronauts to the ISS for the first time since the retirement of the <a href="/wiki/Space_Shuttle" title="Space Shuttle">Space Shuttle</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-127" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-127">&#91;127&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-nasacc_dates3_128-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nasacc_dates3-128">&#91;128&#93;</a></sup> In February 2017 SpaceX announced that two would-be <a href="/wiki/Space_tourism" title="Space tourism">space tourists</a> had put down "significant deposits" for a mission which would see the two tourists fly on board a Dragon capsule around the Moon and back again.\n</p><p>In addition to SpaceX\'s privately funded plans for an eventual <a href="/wiki/Exploration_of_Mars" title="Exploration of Mars">Mars mission</a>, NASA <a href="/wiki/Ames_Research_Center" title="Ames Research Center">Ames Research Center</a> had developed a concept called <a href="/wiki/Red_Dragon_(spacecraft)" class="mw-redirect" title="Red Dragon (spacecraft)">Red Dragon</a>: a low-cost Mars mission that would use <a href="/wiki/Falcon_Heavy" title="Falcon Heavy">Falcon Heavy</a> as the launch vehicle and trans-Martian injection vehicle, and the <a href="/wiki/SpaceX_Dragon" title="SpaceX Dragon">Dragon capsule</a> to <a href="/wiki/Atmospheric_entry" title="Atmospheric entry">enter</a> the <a href="/wiki/Martian_atmosphere" class="mw-redirect" title="Martian atmosphere">Martian atmosphere</a>. The concept was originally envisioned for launch in 2018 as a <a href="/wiki/Discovery_Program" title="Discovery Program">NASA Discovery mission</a>, then alternatively for 2022<sup id="cite_ref-Wall2015_129-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Wall2015-129">&#91;129&#93;</a></sup> The objectives of the mission would be return the samples from Mars to Earth at a fraction of the cost of the NASA own return-sample mission now projected at 6 billion dollars.<sup id="cite_ref-Wall2015_129-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Wall2015-129">&#91;129&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-130" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-130">&#91;130&#93;</a></sup> In September 2017, <a href="/wiki/Elon_Musk" title="Elon Musk">Elon Musk</a> released first prototype images of their space suits to be used in future missions. The suit is in testing phase and it is designed to cope with 2&#160;atm (200&#160;kPa; 29&#160;psi) pressure in vacuum.<sup id="cite_ref-131" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-131">&#91;131&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-132" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-132">&#91;132&#93;</a></sup> The Crew Dragon spacecraft was first sent to space on March 2, 2019.\n</p>\n<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Research_and_development">Research and development</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=SpaceX&amp;action=edit&amp;section=10" title="Edit section: Research and development">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Raptor-test-9-25-2016.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/dd/Raptor-test-9-25-2016.jpg/220px-Raptor-test-9-25-2016.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="147" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/dd/Raptor-test-9-25-2016.jpg/330px-Raptor-test-9-25-2016.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/dd/Raptor-test-9-25-2016.jpg/440px-Raptor-test-9-25-2016.jpg 2x" data-file-width="4752" data-file-height="3168" /></a>  <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Raptor-test-9-25-2016.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>First test firing of a scale Raptor development engine in September 2016 in McGregor, Texas.</div></div></div>\n<p>SpaceX is actively pursuing several different <a href="/wiki/Research_and_development" title="Research and development">research and development</a> programs. Most notable are those intended to develop a fully reusable launch vehicle called <a href="/wiki/SpaceX_Starship" title="SpaceX Starship">Starship</a> and a global telecommunications network called <a href="/wiki/Starlink_(satellite_constellation)" class="mw-redirect" title="Starlink (satellite constellation)">StarLink</a>.\n</p>\n<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Reusable_launch_system">Reusable launch system</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=SpaceX&amp;action=edit&amp;section=11" title="Edit section: Reusable launch system">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>\n<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:SpaceX_ASDS_in_position_prior_to_Falcon_9_Flight_17_carrying_CRS-6_(17127808431).jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/97/SpaceX_ASDS_in_position_prior_to_Falcon_9_Flight_17_carrying_CRS-6_%2817127808431%29.jpg/220px-SpaceX_ASDS_in_position_prior_to_Falcon_9_Flight_17_carrying_CRS-6_%2817127808431%29.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="157" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/97/SpaceX_ASDS_in_position_prior_to_Falcon_9_Flight_17_carrying_CRS-6_%2817127808431%29.jpg/330px-SpaceX_ASDS_in_position_prior_to_Falcon_9_Flight_17_carrying_CRS-6_%2817127808431%29.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/97/SpaceX_ASDS_in_position_prior_to_Falcon_9_Flight_17_carrying_CRS-6_%2817127808431%29.jpg/440px-SpaceX_ASDS_in_position_prior_to_Falcon_9_Flight_17_carrying_CRS-6_%2817127808431%29.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1969" data-file-height="1407" /></a>  <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:SpaceX_ASDS_in_position_prior_to_Falcon_9_Flight_17_carrying_CRS-6_(17127808431).jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div><i><a href="/wiki/Autonomous_spaceport_drone_ship" title="Autonomous spaceport drone ship">Autonomous spaceport drone ship</a></i> in position prior to Falcon 9 Flight 17 carrying CRS-6.</div></div></div>\n<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main articles: <a href="/wiki/SpaceX_reusable_launch_system_development_program" title="SpaceX reusable launch system development program">SpaceX reusable launch system development program</a> and <a href="/wiki/Falcon_9_first-stage_landing_tests" title="Falcon 9 first-stage landing tests">Falcon 9 first-stage landing tests</a></div>\n<p>SpaceX\'s reusable launcher program was publicly announced in 2011 and the design phase was completed in February 2012. The system returns the <a href="/wiki/First_stage_(rocketry)" class="mw-redirect" title="First stage (rocketry)">first stage</a> of a <a href="/wiki/Falcon_9" title="Falcon 9">Falcon 9</a> rocket to a predetermined landing site using only its own propulsion systems.<sup id="cite_ref-pm20120207_133-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-pm20120207-133">&#91;133&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>SpaceX\'s active test program began in late 2012 with testing low-altitude, low-speed aspects of the <a href="/wiki/VTVL" title="VTVL">landing</a> technology. <a href="/wiki/Grasshopper_(rocket)" title="Grasshopper (rocket)">Grasshopper</a> and the Falcon 9 Reusable Development Vehicles (F9R Dev) were experimental <a href="/wiki/Technology-demonstrator" class="mw-redirect" title="Technology-demonstrator">technology-demonstrator</a> <a href="/wiki/Reusable_launch_system" title="Reusable launch system">reusable rockets</a> that performed vertical takeoffs and landings.\n</p><p>High-velocity, high-altitude aspects of the <a href="/wiki/Booster_(rocketry)" title="Booster (rocketry)">booster</a> atmospheric return technology began testing in late 2013 and have continued through 2018, with a 98% success rate to <a href="/wiki/List_of_Falcon_9_and_Falcon_Heavy_launches" title="List of Falcon 9 and Falcon Heavy launches">date</a>. As a result of Elon Musk\'s goal of crafting more cost-effective launch vehicles, SpaceX conceived a method to reuse the first stage of their primary rocket, the <a href="/wiki/Falcon_9" title="Falcon 9">Falcon 9</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-:1_134-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:1-134">&#91;134&#93;</a></sup> by attempting propulsive vertical landings on solid surfaces. Once the company determined that soft landings were feasible by touching down over the Atlantic and Pacific Ocean, they began landing attempts on a solid platform. SpaceX leased and modified several barges to sit out at sea as a target for the returning first stage, converting them to <a href="/wiki/Autonomous_spaceport_drone_ship" title="Autonomous spaceport drone ship">autonomous spaceport drone ships</a> (ASDS). SpaceX first achieved a <a href="/wiki/Falcon_9_Flight_20" class="mw-redirect" title="Falcon 9 Flight 20">successful landing and recovery of a first stage</a> in December 2015,<sup id="cite_ref-135" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-135">&#91;135&#93;</a></sup> and in April 2016, the first stage booster first successfully landed on the ASDS <i><a href="/wiki/Of_Course_I_Still_Love_You" class="mw-redirect" title="Of Course I Still Love You">Of Course I Still Love You</a></i>.<sup id="cite_ref-crs84klanding_136-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-crs84klanding-136">&#91;136&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-crs8hostedlanding_137-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-crs8hostedlanding-137">&#91;137&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>SpaceX continues to carry out first stage landings on every orbital launch that fuel margins allow. By October 2016, following the successful landings, SpaceX indicated they were offering their customers a ten percent price discount if they choose to fly their payload on a reused Falcon 9 first stage.<sup id="cite_ref-sn20161005_138-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-sn20161005-138">&#91;138&#93;</a></sup> On March 30, 2017, SpaceX launched a "flight-proven" Falcon 9 for the <a href="/wiki/SES-10" title="SES-10">SES-10 mission</a>. This was the first time a re-launch of a payload-carrying orbital rocket went back to space.<sup id="cite_ref-:2_67-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:2-67">&#91;67&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-139" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-139">&#91;139&#93;</a></sup> The first stage was recovered and landed on the ASDS <i>Of Course I Still Love You</i> in the Atlantic Ocean, also making it the first landing of a reused orbital class rocket. Elon Musk called the achievement an "incredible milestone in the history of space."<sup id="cite_ref-140" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-140">&#91;140&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-141" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-141">&#91;141&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Starship">Starship</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=SpaceX&amp;action=edit&amp;section=12" title="Edit section: Starship">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>\n<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main articles: <a href="/wiki/SpaceX_Mars_transportation_infrastructure" title="SpaceX Mars transportation infrastructure">SpaceX Mars transportation infrastructure</a>, <a href="/wiki/SpaceX_Starship" title="SpaceX Starship">SpaceX Starship</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Starship_development_history" title="Starship development history">Starship development history</a></div>\n<p>SpaceX is developing a super-heavy lift launch system, <a href="/wiki/SpaceX_Starship" title="SpaceX Starship">Starship</a>. Starship is a <a href="/wiki/Reusable_launch_vehicle" class="mw-redirect" title="Reusable launch vehicle">fully reusable</a> <a href="/wiki/Second_stage" class="mw-redirect" title="Second stage">second stage</a> and <a href="/wiki/Space_vehicle" title="Space vehicle">space vehicle</a> intended to replace all of the company\'s existing launch vehicle hardware by the early 2020s; plus ground infrastructure for rapid launch and relaunch and zero-gravity propellant transfer technology in <a href="/wiki/Low_Earth_orbit" title="Low Earth orbit">low Earth orbit</a> (LEO).\n</p><p>SpaceX initially envisioned a 12-meter-diameter ITS concept in 2016 which was solely aimed at Mars transit and other interplanetary uses. In 2017, SpaceX articulated a smaller 9-meter-diameter BFR to replace all of SpaceX launch service provider capabilities\xe2\x80\x94Earth-orbit, lunar-orbit, interplanetary missions, and potentially, even intercontinental passenger transport on Earth\xe2\x80\x94but do so on a fully reusable set of vehicles with a markedly lower cost structure.<sup id="cite_ref-142" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-142">&#91;142&#93;</a></sup> A large portion of the components on Starship are made of 301 <a href="/wiki/Stainless_steel" title="Stainless steel">stainless steel</a>. Private passenger <a href="/wiki/Yusaku_Maezawa" title="Yusaku Maezawa">Yusaku Maezawa</a> has contracted to <a href="/wiki/Circumlunar_trajectory" title="Circumlunar trajectory">fly around the Moon</a> in Starship in 2023.<sup id="cite_ref-143" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-143">&#91;143&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-144" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-144">&#91;144&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-145" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-145">&#91;145&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Musk\'s long term vision for the company is the development of technology and resources suitable for human colonization on Mars. He has expressed his interest in someday traveling to the planet, stating "I\'d like to die on Mars, just not on impact."<sup id="cite_ref-146" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-146">&#91;146&#93;</a></sup> A rocket every two years or so could provide a base for the people arriving in 2025 after a launch in 2024.<sup id="cite_ref-147" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-147">&#91;147&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-148" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-148">&#91;148&#93;</a></sup> According to Steve Jurvetson, Musk believes that by 2035 at the latest, there will be thousands of rockets flying a million people to Mars, in order to enable a self-sustaining human colony.<sup id="cite_ref-149" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-149">&#91;149&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Other_projects">Other projects</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=SpaceX&amp;action=edit&amp;section=13" title="Edit section: Other projects">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>\n<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main articles: <a href="/wiki/Starlink_(satellite_constellation)" class="mw-redirect" title="Starlink (satellite constellation)">Starlink (satellite constellation)</a> and <a href="/wiki/Hyperloop_pod_competition" title="Hyperloop pod competition">Hyperloop pod competition</a></div>\n<p>In January 2015, SpaceX CEO <a href="/wiki/Elon_Musk" title="Elon Musk">Elon Musk</a> announced the development of <a href="/wiki/SpaceX_satellite_constellation" class="mw-redirect" title="SpaceX satellite constellation">a new satellite constellation</a> to provide global broadband internet service.
