In June 2015 the company asked the federal government for permission to begin testing for a project that aims to build a constellation of 4,425 satellites capable of beaming the Internet to the entire globe, including remote regions which currently do not have Internet access.<sup id="cite_ref-150" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-150">&#91;150&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-151" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-151">&#91;151&#93;</a></sup> The Internet service would use a constellation of 4,425 cross-linked <a href="/wiki/Communications_satellite" title="Communications satellite">communications satellites</a> in 1,100&#160;km orbits. Owned and operated by SpaceX, the goal of the business is to increase profitability and cashflow, to allow SpaceX to build its Mars colony.<sup id="cite_ref-sn20150119_152-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-sn20150119-152">&#91;152&#93;</a></sup> Development began in 2015, initial prototype <a href="/wiki/Flight_test" title="Flight test">test-flight</a> satellites were launched on the SpaceX PAZ mission in 2017. Initial operation of the constellation could begin as early as 2020. As of March&#160;2017<sup class="plainlinks noexcerpt noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;"><a class="external text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=SpaceX&amp;action=edit">&#91;update&#93;</a></sup>, SpaceX filed with the <a href="/wiki/FCC" class="mw-redirect" title="FCC">US regulatory authorities</a> plans to field a constellation of an additional 7,518 "<a href="/wiki/V-band" class="mw-redirect" title="V-band">V-band</a> satellites in non-<a href="/wiki/Geosynchronous_orbit" title="Geosynchronous orbit">geosynchronous orbits</a> to provide communications services" in an electromagnetic spectrum that had not previously been "heavily employed for commercial communications services". Called the "V-band low-Earth-orbit (VLEO) constellation", it would consist of "7,518 satellites to follow the [earlier] proposed 4,425 satellites that would function in <a href="/wiki/Ka-band" class="mw-redirect" title="Ka-band">Ka-</a> and <a href="/wiki/Ku-band" class="mw-redirect" title="Ku-band">Ku-band</a>".<sup id="cite_ref-153" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-153">&#91;153&#93;</a></sup>\nIn February 2019, SpaceX formed a sibling company, <b>SpaceX Services, Inc.</b>, to license the manufacture and deployment of up to 1,000,000 <a href="/wiki/Fixed_station" title="Fixed station">fixed</a> <a href="/wiki/Satellite_earth_station" class="mw-redirect" title="Satellite earth station">satellite earth stations</a> that will communicate with its Starlink system.<sup id="cite_ref-fcc20190201_154-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-fcc20190201-154">&#91;154&#93;</a></sup> In May 2019, SpaceX launched the first batch of 60 satellites aboard a Falcon 9 from Cape Canaveral, FL.<sup id="cite_ref-155" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-155">&#91;155&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>In June 2015, SpaceX announced that they would sponsor a <a href="/wiki/Hyperloop" title="Hyperloop">Hyperloop</a> <a href="/wiki/Hyperloop_pod_competition" title="Hyperloop pod competition">competition</a>, and would build a 1-mile-long (1.6&#160;km) <a href="/wiki/Scale_model" title="Scale model">subscale</a> test track near SpaceX\'s headquarters for the competitive events.<sup id="cite_ref-nbc20150615_156-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nbc20150615-156">&#91;156&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-spacex-competition201506_157-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-spacex-competition201506-157">&#91;157&#93;</a></sup> The first competitive event was held at the track in January 2017, the second in August 2017 and the third in December 2018.<sup id="cite_ref-sxhyperloop20170910_158-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-sxhyperloop20170910-158">&#91;158&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-bi20170127_159-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-bi20170127-159">&#91;159&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-geekwire20170827_160-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-geekwire20170827-160">&#91;160&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Infrastructure">Infrastructure</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=SpaceX&amp;action=edit&amp;section=14" title="Edit section: Infrastructure">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Entrance_to_SpaceX_headquarters.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/86/Entrance_to_SpaceX_headquarters.jpg/220px-Entrance_to_SpaceX_headquarters.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="330" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/86/Entrance_to_SpaceX_headquarters.jpg/330px-Entrance_to_SpaceX_headquarters.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/86/Entrance_to_SpaceX_headquarters.jpg/440px-Entrance_to_SpaceX_headquarters.jpg 2x" data-file-width="2848" data-file-height="4272" /></a>  <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Entrance_to_SpaceX_headquarters.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>The company\'s headquarters, located in <a href="/wiki/Hawthorne,_California" title="Hawthorne, California">Hawthorne, California</a>.</div></div></div>\n<p>SpaceX is <a href="/wiki/Headquarter" class="mw-redirect" title="Headquarter">headquartered</a> in Hawthorne, California, which also serves as its primary manufacturing plant. The company owns a test site in Texas and operates three launch sites, with another under development. SpaceX also operates regional offices in Redmond, Texas, Virginia, and Washington, D.C.<sup id="cite_ref-about_45-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-about-45">&#91;45&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h3><span id="Headquarters.2C_manufacturing_and_refurbishment_facilities"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="Headquarters,_manufacturing_and_refurbishment_facilities">Headquarters, manufacturing and refurbishment facilities</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=SpaceX&amp;action=edit&amp;section=15" title="Edit section: Headquarters, manufacturing and refurbishment facilities">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>\n<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Falcon_9_rocket_cores_under_construction_at_SpaceX_Hawthorne_facility_(16846994851).jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e8/Falcon_9_rocket_cores_under_construction_at_SpaceX_Hawthorne_facility_%2816846994851%29.jpg/220px-Falcon_9_rocket_cores_under_construction_at_SpaceX_Hawthorne_facility_%2816846994851%29.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="150" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e8/Falcon_9_rocket_cores_under_construction_at_SpaceX_Hawthorne_facility_%2816846994851%29.jpg/330px-Falcon_9_rocket_cores_under_construction_at_SpaceX_Hawthorne_facility_%2816846994851%29.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e8/Falcon_9_rocket_cores_under_construction_at_SpaceX_Hawthorne_facility_%2816846994851%29.jpg/440px-Falcon_9_rocket_cores_under_construction_at_SpaceX_Hawthorne_facility_%2816846994851%29.jpg 2x" data-file-width="2048" data-file-height="1392" /></a>  <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Falcon_9_rocket_cores_under_construction_at_SpaceX_Hawthorne_facility_(16846994851).jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div><a href="/wiki/Falcon_9_v1.1" title="Falcon 9 v1.1">Falcon 9 v1.1</a> rocket cores under construction at the SpaceX Hawthorne facility, November 2014.</div></div></div>\n<p>SpaceX Headquarters is located in the <a href="/wiki/Los_Angeles" title="Los Angeles">Los Angeles</a> suburb of <a href="/wiki/Hawthorne,_California" title="Hawthorne, California">Hawthorne, California</a>. The large three-story facility, originally built by <a href="/wiki/Northrop_Corporation" title="Northrop Corporation">Northrop Corporation</a> to build <a href="/wiki/Boeing_747" title="Boeing 747">Boeing 747</a> fuselages,<sup id="cite_ref-pm_161-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-pm-161">&#91;161&#93;</a></sup> houses SpaceX\'s office space, mission control, and, as of 2018, all vehicle manufacturing. In March 2018, SpaceX indicated that it would manufacture its next-generation, 9&#160;m (30&#160;ft)-diameter launch vehicle, the <a href="/wiki/SpaceX_Starship" title="SpaceX Starship">Starship</a> at a new facility on the <a href="/wiki/Los_Angeles,_California" class="mw-redirect" title="Los Angeles, California">Los Angeles</a> waterfront in the <a href="/wiki/San_Pedro,_Los_Angeles" title="San Pedro, Los Angeles">San Pedro</a> area. The company had leased an 18-acre (73,000&#160;m<sup>2</sup>) site near Berth 240 in the Los Angeles, however in January 2019 the lease was canceled and the construction of Starship moved to a new site in South Texas.<sup id="cite_ref-ars20180319_162-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ars20180319-162">&#91;162&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-163" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-163">&#91;163&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-164" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-164">&#91;164&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>The area has one of the largest concentrations of aerospace headquarters, facilities, and/or subsidiaries in the U.S., including <a href="/wiki/Boeing" title="Boeing">Boeing</a>/McDonnell Douglas main satellite building campuses, <a href="/wiki/Aerospace_Corp." class="mw-redirect" title="Aerospace Corp.">Aerospace Corp.</a>, <a href="/wiki/Raytheon" title="Raytheon">Raytheon</a>, NASA\'s <a href="/wiki/Jet_Propulsion_Laboratory" title="Jet Propulsion Laboratory">Jet Propulsion Laboratory</a>, <a href="/wiki/Air_Force_Space_Command" title="Air Force Space Command">Air Force Space Command</a>\'s <a href="/wiki/Space_and_Missile_Systems_Center" title="Space and Missile Systems Center">Space and Missile Systems Center</a> at <a href="/wiki/Los_Angeles_Air_Force_Base" title="Los Angeles Air Force Base">Los Angeles Air Force Base</a>, <a href="/wiki/Lockheed_Martin" title="Lockheed Martin">Lockheed Martin</a>, <a href="/wiki/BAE_Systems" title="BAE Systems">BAE Systems</a>, <a href="/wiki/Northrop_Grumman" title="Northrop Grumman">Northrop Grumman</a>, and <a href="/wiki/AECOM" title="AECOM">AECOM</a>, etc., with a large pool of aerospace engineers and recent college engineering graduates.<sup id="cite_ref-pm_161-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-pm-161">&#91;161&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>SpaceX utilizes a high degree of <a href="/wiki/Vertical_integration" title="Vertical integration">vertical integration</a> in the production of its rockets and rocket engines.<sup id="cite_ref-A&amp;Ssmithsonian201201_29-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-A&amp;Ssmithsonian201201-29">&#91;29&#93;</a></sup> SpaceX builds its <a href="/wiki/Rocket_engine" title="Rocket engine">rocket engines</a>, <a href="/wiki/Launch_vehicle" title="Launch vehicle">rocket stages</a>, <a href="/wiki/Spacecraft" title="Spacecraft">spacecraft</a>, principal <a href="/wiki/Avionics" title="Avionics">avionics</a> and all <a href="/wiki/Embedded_software" title="Embedded software">software</a> in-house in their Hawthorne facility, which is unusual for the aerospace industry. Nevertheless, SpaceX still has over 3,000 suppliers with some 1,100 of those delivering to SpaceX nearly weekly.<sup id="cite_ref-AtlanticCouncil20140604q2_165-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-AtlanticCouncil20140604q2-165">&#91;165&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>In June 2017, SpaceX announced they would construct a facility on 0.88 hectares (2.17 acres) in <a href="/wiki/Port_Canaveral" title="Port Canaveral">Port Canaveral</a> Florida for refurbishment and storage of previously flown Falcon 9 and Falcon Heavy booster cores.<sup id="cite_ref-166" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-166">&#91;166&#93;</a></sup><sup class="noprint Inline-Template" style="margin-left:0.1em; white-space:nowrap;">&#91;<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Dates_and_numbers#Chronological_items" title="Wikipedia:Manual of Style/Dates and numbers"><span title="The text near this tag is dated. (May 2018)">needs update</span></a></i>&#93;</sup>\n</p>\n<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Development_and_test_facilities">Development and test facilities</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=SpaceX&amp;action=edit&amp;section=16" title="Edit section: Development and test facilities">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>\n<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:SpaceX_Engine_Test_Bunker.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4c/SpaceX_Engine_Test_Bunker.jpg/220px-SpaceX_Engine_Test_Bunker.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="174" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4c/SpaceX_Engine_Test_Bunker.jpg/330px-SpaceX_Engine_Test_Bunker.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4c/SpaceX_Engine_Test_Bunker.jpg/440px-SpaceX_Engine_Test_Bunker.jpg 2x" data-file-width="2972" data-file-height="2353" /></a>  <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:SpaceX_Engine_Test_Bunker.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>SpaceX McGregor engine test bunker, September 2012</div></div></div>\n<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main article: <a href="/wiki/SpaceX_Rocket_Development_and_Test_Facility" class="mw-redirect" title="SpaceX Rocket Development and Test Facility">SpaceX Rocket Development and Test Facility</a></div>\n<p>SpaceX operates their first Rocket Development and Test Facility in <a href="/wiki/McGregor,_Texas" title="McGregor, Texas">McGregor, Texas</a>. All SpaceX rocket engines are tested on <a href="/wiki/Rocket_engine_test_facility" title="Rocket engine test facility">rocket test stands</a>, and low-altitude <a href="/wiki/VTVL" title="VTVL">VTVL</a> flight testing of the Falcon 9 <a href="/wiki/Grasshopper_(rocket)" title="Grasshopper (rocket)">Grasshopper</a> v1.0 and <a href="/wiki/F9R_Dev1" class="mw-redirect" title="F9R Dev1">F9R Dev1</a> test vehicles in 2013\xe2\x80\x932014 were carried out at McGregor. 2019 low-altitude VTVL testing of the much larger 9-meter (30&#160;ft)-diameter <i><a href="/wiki/Starship_test_flight_rocket" class="mw-redirect" title="Starship test flight rocket">"Starhopper"</a></i> is planned to occur at the <a href="/wiki/SpaceX_South_Texas_Launch_Site" title="SpaceX South Texas Launch Site">SpaceX South Texas Launch Site</a> near <a href="/wiki/Brownsville,_Texas" title="Brownsville, Texas">Brownsville, Texas</a>, which is currently under construction.<sup id="cite_ref-trati20181224_167-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-trati20181224-167">&#91;167&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-sn20181224_168-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-sn20181224-168">&#91;168&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-mw20190110_169-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-mw20190110-169">&#91;169&#93;</a></sup> On January 23, 2019, strong winds at the Texas test launch site blew over the nose cone over the first test article rocket, causing delays that will take weeks to repair according to SpaceX representatives.<sup id="cite_ref-170" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-170">&#91;170&#93;</a></sup> In the event, SpaceX decided to forego building another nose cone for the first test article, because at the low velocities planned for that rocket, it was unnecessary.\n</p><p>The company purchased the McGregor facilities from <a href="/wiki/Beal_Aerospace" title="Beal Aerospace">Beal Aerospace</a>, where it refitted the largest test stand for <a href="/wiki/Falcon_9" title="Falcon 9">Falcon 9</a> engine testing. SpaceX has made a number of improvements to the facility since purchase, and has also extended the acreage by purchasing several pieces of adjacent farmland. In 2011, the company announced plans to upgrade the facility for launch testing a VTVL rocket,<sup id="cite_ref-satspot20110926_50-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-satspot20110926-50">&#91;50&#93;</a></sup> and then constructed a half-acre concrete launch facility in 2012 to support the Grasshopper test flight program.<sup id="cite_ref-sfn20120709_51-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-sfn20120709-51">&#91;51&#93;</a></sup> As of October&#160;2012<sup class="plainlinks noexcerpt noprint asof-tag update" style="display:none;"><a class="external text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=SpaceX&amp;action=edit">&#91;update&#93;</a></sup>, the McGregor facility had seven test stands that are operated "18 hours a day, six days a week"<sup id="cite_ref-wired20121010_171-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-wired20121010-171">&#91;171&#93;</a></sup> and is building more test stands because production is ramping up and the company has a large <a href="/wiki/List_of_Falcon_9_launches#Launch_Manifest" class="mw-redirect" title="List of Falcon 9 launches">manifest</a> in the next several years. <sup class="noprint Inline-Template" style="margin-left:0.1em; white-space:nowrap;">&#91;<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Manual_of_Style/Dates_and_numbers#Chronological_items" title="Wikipedia:Manual of Style/Dates and numbers"><span title="The text near this tag is dated. (January 2013)">needs update</span></a></i>&#93;</sup>\n</p><p>In addition to routine testing, Dragon capsules (following recovery after an orbital mission), are shipped to McGregor for de-fueling, cleanup, and refurbishment for reuse in future missions.\n</p>\n<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Launch_facilities">Launch facilities</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=SpaceX&amp;action=edit&amp;section=17" title="Edit section: Launch facilities">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>\n<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main article: <a href="/wiki/SpaceX_launch_facilities" title="SpaceX launch facilities">SpaceX launch facilities</a></div>\n<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Launch_of_Falcon_9_carrying_CASSIOPE_(130929-F-ET475-012).jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/58/Launch_of_Falcon_9_carrying_CASSIOPE_%28130929-F-ET475-012%29.jpg/220px-Launch_of_Falcon_9_carrying_CASSIOPE_%28130929-F-ET475-012%29.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="147" class="thumbimage" 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/58/Launch_of_Falcon_9_carrying_CASSIOPE_%28130929-F-ET475-012%29.jpg/440px-Launch_of_Falcon_9_carrying_CASSIOPE_%28130929-F-ET475-012%29.jpg 2x" data-file-width="2871" data-file-height="1914" /></a>  <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Launch_of_Falcon_9_carrying_CASSIOPE_(130929-F-ET475-012).jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>SpaceX west coast launch facility at <a href="/wiki/Vandenberg_Air_Force_Base" title="Vandenberg Air Force Base">Vandenberg Air Force Base</a>, during the launch of CASSIOPE, September 2013.</div></div></div>\n<p>SpaceX currently operates three <a href="/wiki/Orbital_spaceflight" title="Orbital spaceflight">orbital</a> launch sites, at <a href="/wiki/Cape_Canaveral" title="Cape Canaveral">Cape Canaveral</a>, <a href="/wiki/Vandenberg_Air_Force_Base" title="Vandenberg Air Force Base">Vandenberg Air Force Base</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Kennedy_Space_Center" title="Kennedy Space Center">Kennedy Space Center</a>, and is under construction on a fourth in Brownsville, Texas. SpaceX has indicated that they see a niche for each of the four orbital facilities and that they have sufficient launch business to fill each pad.<sup id="cite_ref-sn20130802_172-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-sn20130802-172">&#91;172&#93;</a></sup> The Vandenberg launch site enables highly inclined orbits (66\xe2\x80\x93145\xc2\xb0), while Cape Canaveral enables orbits of medium inclination, up to 51.6\xc2\xb0.<sup id="cite_ref-173" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-173">&#91;173&#93;</a></sup> Before it was retired, all <a href="/wiki/Falcon_1" title="Falcon 1">Falcon 1</a> launches took place at the <a href="/wiki/Ronald_Reagan_Ballistic_Missile_Defense_Test_Site" title="Ronald Reagan Ballistic Missile Defense Test Site">Ronald Reagan Ballistic Missile Defense Test Site</a> on <a href="/wiki/Omelek_Island" title="Omelek Island">Omelek Island</a>.\n</p>\n<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Cape_Canaveral">Cape Canaveral</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=SpaceX&amp;action=edit&amp;section=18" title="Edit section: Cape Canaveral">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>\n<p><a href="/wiki/Cape_Canaveral_Air_Force_Station_Space_Launch_Complex_40" title="Cape Canaveral Air Force Station Space Launch Complex 40">Cape Canaveral Air Force Station Space Launch Complex 40</a> (SLC-40) is used for Falcon 9 launches to low Earth and geostationary orbits. SLC-40 is not capable of supporting Falcon Heavy launches. As part of SpaceX\'s booster reusability program, the former Launch Complex 13 at Cape Canaveral, now renamed <a href="/wiki/Landing_Zone_1" class="mw-redirect" title="Landing Zone 1">Landing Zone 1</a>, has been designated for use for Falcon 9 <a href="/wiki/Falcon_9_first-stage_landing_tests" title="Falcon 9 first-stage landing tests">first-stage booster landings</a>.\n</p>\n<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:ORBCOMM-2_First-Stage_Landing_(23271687254).jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/64/ORBCOMM-2_First-Stage_Landing_%2823271687254%29.jpg/220px-ORBCOMM-2_First-Stage_Landing_%2823271687254%29.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="147" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/64/ORBCOMM-2_First-Stage_Landing_%2823271687254%29.jpg/330px-ORBCOMM-2_First-Stage_Landing_%2823271687254%29.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/64/ORBCOMM-2_First-Stage_Landing_%2823271687254%29.jpg/440px-ORBCOMM-2_First-Stage_Landing_%2823271687254%29.jpg 2x" data-file-width="3000" data-file-height="2000" /></a>  <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:ORBCOMM-2_First-Stage_Landing_(23271687254).jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div><a href="/wiki/Falcon_9_Flight_20" class="mw-redirect" title="Falcon 9 Flight 20">Falcon 9 Flight 20</a> landing on <a href="/wiki/Landing_Zone_1" class="mw-redirect" title="Landing Zone 1">Landing Zone 1</a> in December 2015</div></div></div>\n<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Vandenberg">Vandenberg</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=SpaceX&amp;action=edit&amp;section=19" title="Edit section: Vandenberg">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>\n<p><a href="/wiki/Vandenberg_Air_Force_Base_Space_Launch_Complex_4#SLC-4E" title="Vandenberg Air Force Base Space Launch Complex 4">Vandenberg Air Force Base Space Launch Complex 4 East</a> (SLC-4E) is used for payloads to polar orbits. The Vandenberg site can launch both Falcon 9 and Falcon Heavy,<sup id="cite_ref-nsf20110405_174-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nsf20110405-174">&#91;174&#93;</a></sup> but cannot launch to low inclination orbits. The neighboring SLC-4W has been converted to Landing Zone 4, where SpaceX successfully landed one Falcon 9 first-stage booster, in October 2018.<sup id="cite_ref-175" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-175">&#91;175&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Kennedy_Space_Center">Kennedy Space Center</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=SpaceX&amp;action=edit&amp;section=20" title="Edit section: Kennedy Space Center">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>\n<p>On April 14, 2014, SpaceX signed a 20-year lease for <a href="/wiki/Kennedy_Space_Center_Launch_Complex_39" title="Kennedy Space Center Launch Complex 39">Launch Pad 39A</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-176" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-176">&#91;176&#93;</a></sup> The pad was subsequently modified to support <a href="/wiki/Falcon_9" title="Falcon 9">Falcon 9</a> and <a href="/wiki/Falcon_Heavy" title="Falcon Heavy">Falcon Heavy</a> launches. SpaceX has launched 13 Falcon 9 missions from <a href="/wiki/Kennedy_Space_Center_Launch_Complex_39" title="Kennedy Space Center Launch Complex 39">Launch Pad 39A</a>, the latest of which was launched on January 19, 2020.<sup id="cite_ref-:7_177-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:7-177">&#91;177&#93;</a></sup>SpaceX intends to launch the first crewed missions to the ISS from <a href="/wiki/Kennedy_Space_Center_Launch_Complex_39" title="Kennedy Space Center Launch Complex 39">Launch Pad 39A</a> in 2019.<sup id="cite_ref-178" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-178">&#91;178&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Brownsville">Brownsville</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=SpaceX&amp;action=edit&amp;section=21" title="Edit section: Brownsville">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>\n<p>In August 2014, SpaceX announced they would be building a <a href="/wiki/SpaceX_South_Texas_Launch_Site" title="SpaceX South Texas Launch Site">commercial-only launch facility</a> at <a href="/wiki/Brownsville,_Texas" title="Brownsville, Texas">Brownsville, Texas</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-179" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-179">&#91;179&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-180" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-180">&#91;180&#93;</a></sup> The <a href="/wiki/Federal_Aviation_Administration" title="Federal Aviation Administration">Federal Aviation Administration</a> released a draft <a href="/wiki/Environmental_impact_statement" title="Environmental impact statement">Environmental Impact Statement</a> for the proposed Texas facility in April 2013, and "found that \'no impacts would occur\' that would force the Federal Aviation Administration to deny SpaceX a permit for rocket operations,"<sup id="cite_ref-bh201304_181-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-bh201304-181">&#91;181&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-bh201304_181-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-bh201304-181">&#91;181&#93;</a></sup> and issued the permit in July 2014.<sup id="cite_ref-182" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-182">&#91;182&#93;</a></sup> SpaceX started construction on the new launch facility in 2014 with production ramping up in the latter half of 2015,<sup id="cite_ref-sn20140922_183-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-sn20140922-183">&#91;183&#93;</a></sup> with the first <a href="/wiki/Suborbital_spaceflight" class="mw-redirect" title="Suborbital spaceflight">suborbital</a> launches from the facility in 2019.<sup id="cite_ref-trati20181224_167-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-trati20181224-167">&#91;167&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-sn20181224_168-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-sn20181224-168">&#91;168&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-tsr20130401_184-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-tsr20130401-184">&#91;184&#93;</a></sup> Real estate packages at the location have been named by SpaceX with names based on the theme "<a href="/wiki/Mars_Crossing" title="Mars Crossing">Mars Crossing</a>".<sup id="cite_ref-185" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-185">&#91;185&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-186" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-186">&#91;186&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Satellite_prototyping_facility">Satellite prototyping facility</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=SpaceX&amp;action=edit&amp;section=22" title="Edit section: Satellite prototyping facility">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>\n<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Further information: <a href="/wiki/Starlink_(satellite_constellation)" class="mw-redirect" title="Starlink (satellite constellation)">Starlink (satellite constellation)</a></div>\n<p>In January 2015, SpaceX announced it would be entering the satellite production business and global satellite internet business. The first satellite facility is a 30,000-square-foot (2,800&#160;m<sup>2</sup>) office building located in Redmond, Washington. As of January 2017, a second facility in Redmond was acquired with 40,625 square feet (3,774.2&#160;m<sup>2</sup>) and has become a research and development lab for the satellites.<sup id="cite_ref-187" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-187">&#91;187&#93;</a></sup> In July 2016, SpaceX acquired an additional 8,000 square feet (740&#160;m<sup>2</sup>) creative space in <a href="/wiki/Irvine,_California" title="Irvine, California">Irvine, California</a> (Orange County) to focus on satellite communications.<sup id="cite_ref-188" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-188">&#91;188&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Launch_contracts">Launch contracts</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=SpaceX&amp;action=edit&amp;section=23" title="Edit section: Launch contracts">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>\n<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Further information: <a href="/wiki/List_of_Falcon_9_and_Falcon_Heavy_launches" title="List of Falcon 9 and Falcon Heavy launches">List of Falcon 9 and Falcon Heavy launches</a></div>\n<p>SpaceX won demonstration and actual supply contracts from <a href="/wiki/NASA" title="NASA">NASA</a> for the <a href="/wiki/International_Space_Station" title="International Space Station">International Space Station</a> (ISS) with technology the company developed. SpaceX is also certified for <a href="/wiki/US_military" class="mw-redirect" title="US military">US military</a> launches of <a href="/wiki/Evolved_Expendable_Launch_Vehicle" class="mw-redirect" title="Evolved Expendable Launch Vehicle">Evolved Expendable Launch Vehicle</a>-class (EELV) payloads. With approximately 30 missions on manifest for 2018 alone, SpaceX represents over $12 billion under contract.<sup id="cite_ref-about_45-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-about-45">&#91;45&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="NASA_contracts">NASA contracts</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=SpaceX&amp;action=edit&amp;section=24" title="Edit section: NASA contracts">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>\n<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="COTS">COTS</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=SpaceX&amp;action=edit&amp;section=25" title="Edit section: COTS">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>\n<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:COTS2_Dragon_is_berthed.jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/cf/COTS2_Dragon_is_berthed.jpg/220px-COTS2_Dragon_is_berthed.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="183" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/cf/COTS2_Dragon_is_berthed.jpg/330px-COTS2_Dragon_is_berthed.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/cf/COTS2_Dragon_is_berthed.jpg/440px-COTS2_Dragon_is_berthed.jpg 2x" data-file-width="3402" data-file-height="2832" /></a>  <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:COTS2_Dragon_is_berthed.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>The COTS 2 Dragon is berthed to the ISS by <a href="/wiki/Canadarm2" class="mw-redirect" title="Canadarm2">Canadarm2</a>.</div></div></div>\n<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Commercial_Orbital_Transportation_Services" title="Commercial Orbital Transportation Services">Commercial Orbital Transportation Services</a></div>\n<p>In 2006, NASA announced that SpaceX had won a NASA Commercial Orbital Transportation Services (COTS) Phase 1 contract to demonstrate cargo delivery to the ISS, with a possible contract option for crew transport.<sup id="cite_ref-189" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-189">&#91;189&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-SpaceX_presser_20060818_190-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-SpaceX_presser_20060818-190">&#91;190&#93;</a></sup> This contract, designed by NASA to provide "seed money" through Space Act Agreements for developing new capabilities, NASA paid SpaceX $396 million to develop the cargo configuration of the Dragon spacecraft, while SpaceX self-invested more than $500 million to develop the Falcon 9 launch vehicle.<sup id="cite_ref-191" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-191">&#91;191&#93;</a></sup> These <a href="/wiki/Space_Act_Agreement" title="Space Act Agreement">Space Act Agreements</a> have been shown to have saved NASA millions of dollars in development costs, making rocket development ~4-10 times cheaper than if produced by NASA alone.<sup id="cite_ref-:5_94-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:5-94">&#91;94&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>In December 2010, the launch of the <a href="/wiki/COTS_Demo_Flight_1" class="mw-redirect" title="COTS Demo Flight 1">COTS Demo Flight 1</a> mission, SpaceX became the first private company to successfully launch, orbit and recover a spacecraft.<sup id="cite_ref-spaceflight_20101208_192-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-spaceflight_20101208-192">&#91;192&#93;</a></sup> Dragon was successfully deployed into orbit, circled the Earth twice, and then made a controlled re-entry burn for a splashdown in the Pacific Ocean. With Dragon\'s safe recovery, SpaceX became the first private company to launch, orbit, and recover a spacecraft; prior to this mission, only government agencies had been able to recover orbital spacecraft.\n</p><p><a href="/wiki/COTS_Demo_Flight_2" class="mw-redirect" title="COTS Demo Flight 2">COTS Demo Flight 2</a> launched in May 2012, in which Dragon successfully berthed with the ISS, marking the first time that a private spacecraft had accomplished this feat.<sup id="cite_ref-193" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-193">&#91;193&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-194" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-194">&#91;194&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Commercial_cargo">Commercial cargo</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=SpaceX&amp;action=edit&amp;section=26" title="Edit section: Commercial cargo">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>\n<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Commercial_Resupply_Services" title="Commercial Resupply Services">Commercial Resupply Services</a></div>\n<p>Commercial Resupply Services (CRS) are a series of contracts awarded by NASA from 2008 to 2016 for delivery of cargo and supplies to the ISS on commercially operated spacecraft. The first CRS contracts were signed in 2008 and awarded $1.6 billion to SpaceX for 12 cargo transport missions, covering deliveries to 2016.<sup id="cite_ref-COTSwon_195-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-COTSwon-195">&#91;195&#93;</a></sup> <a href="/wiki/SpaceX_CRS-1" title="SpaceX CRS-1">SpaceX CRS-1</a>, the first of the 12 planned resupply missions, launched in October 2012, achieved orbit, berthed and remained on station for 20 days, before <a href="/wiki/Atmospheric_re-entry" class="mw-redirect" title="Atmospheric re-entry">re-entering the atmosphere</a> and splashing down in the Pacific Ocean.<sup id="cite_ref-nasa20121028_196-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nasa20121028-196">&#91;196&#93;</a></sup> CRS missions have flown approximately twice a year to the ISS since then. In 2015, NASA extended the Phase 1 contracts by ordering an additional three resupply flights from SpaceX.<sup id="cite_ref-197" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-197">&#91;197&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-198" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-198">&#91;198&#93;</a></sup> After further extensions late in 2015, SpaceX is currently scheduled to fly a total of 20 missions.<sup id="cite_ref-199" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-199">&#91;199&#93;</a></sup> A second phase of contracts (known as <a href="/wiki/Commercial_Resupply_Services" title="Commercial Resupply Services">CRS-2</a>) were solicited and proposed in 2014. They were awarded in January 2016, for cargo transport flights beginning in 2019 and expected to last through 2024.\n</p>\n<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Commercial_crew">Commercial crew</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=SpaceX&amp;action=edit&amp;section=27" title="Edit section: Commercial crew">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>\n<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:SpaceX_Dragon_v2_Pad_Abort_Vehicle_(16661791299).jpg" class="image"><img alt="" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e2/SpaceX_Dragon_v2_Pad_Abort_Vehicle_%2816661791299%29.jpg/220px-SpaceX_Dragon_v2_Pad_Abort_Vehicle_%2816661791299%29.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="165" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e2/SpaceX_Dragon_v2_Pad_Abort_Vehicle_%2816661791299%29.jpg/330px-SpaceX_Dragon_v2_Pad_Abort_Vehicle_%2816661791299%29.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e2/SpaceX_Dragon_v2_Pad_Abort_Vehicle_%2816661791299%29.jpg/440px-SpaceX_Dragon_v2_Pad_Abort_Vehicle_%2816661791299%29.jpg 2x" data-file-width="2640" data-file-height="1980" /></a>  <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:SpaceX_Dragon_v2_Pad_Abort_Vehicle_(16661791299).jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>Crew Dragon undergoing testing prior to flight</div></div></div>\n<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Commercial_Crew_Development" title="Commercial Crew Development">Commercial Crew Development</a></div>\n<p>The Commercial Crew Development (CCDev) program intends to develop commercially operated spacecraft that are capable of delivering astronauts to the ISS. SpaceX did not win a <a href="/wiki/Space_Act_Agreement" title="Space Act Agreement">Space Act Agreement</a> in the first round (CCDev 1), but during the second round (CCDev 2), NASA awarded SpaceX with a contract worth $75 million to further develop their <a href="/wiki/Launch_escape_system" title="Launch escape system">launch escape system</a>, test a crew accommodations mock-up, and to further progress their Falcon/Dragon crew transportation design.<sup id="cite_ref-Space_Abort_System_20111028_200-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Space_Abort_System_20111028-200">&#91;200&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-201" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-201">&#91;201&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-aw20110422_202-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-aw20110422-202">&#91;202&#93;</a></sup> The CCDev program later became Commercial Crew Integrated Capability (<a href="/wiki/CCiCap" class="mw-redirect" title="CCiCap">CCiCap</a>), and in August 2012, NASA announced that SpaceX had been awarded $440 million to continue development and testing of its <a href="/wiki/Dragon_2" title="Dragon 2">Dragon 2</a> spacecraft.<sup id="cite_ref-August2012_203-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-August2012-203">&#91;203&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-204" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-204">&#91;204&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>In September 2014, NASA chose SpaceX and Boeing as the two companies that will be funded to develop systems to transport U.S. crews to and from the ISS. SpaceX won $2.6 billion to complete and certify Dragon 2 by 2017. The contracts include at least one crewed flight test with at least one NASA astronaut aboard. Once Crew Dragon achieves NASA certification, the contract requires SpaceX to conduct at least two, and as many as six, crewed missions to the space station.<sup id="cite_ref-September2014_205-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-September2014-205">&#91;205&#93;</a></sup> In early 2017, SpaceX was awarded four additional crewed missions to the ISS from NASA to shuttle astronauts back and forth.<sup id="cite_ref-206" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-206">&#91;206&#93;</a></sup> In early 2019, SpaceX successfully conducted a test flight of Crew Dragon, which it docked (instead of Dragon 1\'s method of berthing using Canada arm 2) and then splashed down in the Atlantic Ocean.\n</p>\n<h6><span class="mw-headline" id="Commercial_Crew_Progress">Commercial Crew Progress</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=SpaceX&amp;action=edit&amp;section=28" title="Edit section: Commercial Crew Progress">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h6>\n<p>September 16, 2014 - NASA selected SpaceX\xe2\x80\x99s Falcon 9 launch vehicle and Dragon spacecraft to fly American astronauts to the International Space Station under the Commercial Crew Program.<sup id="cite_ref-207" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-207">&#91;207&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>May 6, 2015 - Just after 9 am ET, SpaceX completed the first key flight test of its Crew Dragon spacecraft, a vehicle designed to carry astronauts to and from space. The successful Pad Abort Test was the first flight test of SpaceX\xe2\x80\x99s revolutionary launch abort system, and the data captured here will be critical in preparing Crew Dragon for its first human missions.<sup id="cite_ref-208" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-208">&#91;208&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>August 3, 2018 - NASA announced the first four astronauts who will launch aboard Crew Dragon to the International Space Station.  Bob Behnken and Doug Hurley will be the first two NASA astronauts to fly in the Dragon spacecraft.<sup id="cite_ref-209" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-209">&#91;209&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>March 2, 2019 - Demo-1 test flight without crew on board the spacecraft is intended to demonstrate SpaceX\xe2\x80\x99s capabilities to safely and reliably fly astronauts to and from the International Space Station.<sup id="cite_ref-210" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-210">&#91;210&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>March 3, 2019 - Crew Dragon docked with the ISS at 3:02 a.m. PST, becoming the first American spacecraft to autonomously dock with the orbiting laboratory.<sup id="cite_ref-211" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-211">&#91;211&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>March 8, 2019 - Crew Dragon splashed down in the Atlantic Ocean at 5:45 a.m. PST, completing the spacecraft\'s first mission to the International Space Station.<sup id="cite_ref-212" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-212">&#91;212&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>January 19, 2020 - Crew Dragon test capsule was launched in an atmospheric flight to conduct a separation and abort scenario in the <a href="/wiki/Troposphere" title="Troposphere">troposphere</a> at <a href="/wiki/Transonic" title="Transonic">transonic</a> velocities, at <a href="/wiki/Max_q" title="Max q">max Q</a>, where the vehicle experiences maximum aerodynamic pressure. The Crew Dragon splashed down at 15:38 UTC just off the Florida coast in the Atlantic Ocean.<sup id="cite_ref-:7_177-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:7-177">&#91;177&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="US_Defense_contracts">US Defense contracts</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=SpaceX&amp;action=edit&amp;section=29" title="Edit section: US Defense contracts">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>\n<p>In 2005, SpaceX announced that it had been awarded an <a href="/wiki/IDIQ" title="IDIQ">Indefinite Delivery/Indefinite Quantity</a> (IDIQ), allowing the <a href="/wiki/United_States_Air_Force" title="United States Air Force">United States Air Force</a> to purchase up to $100 million worth of launches from the company.<sup id="cite_ref-213" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-213">&#91;213&#93;</a></sup> In April 2008, <a href="/wiki/NASA" title="NASA">NASA</a> announced that it had awarded an IDIQ Launch Services contract to SpaceX for up to $1 billion, depending on the number of missions awarded. The contract covers launch services ordered by June 2010, for launches through December 2012.<sup id="cite_ref-NASA_presser_20080422_214-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-NASA_presser_20080422-214">&#91;214&#93;</a></sup> Musk stated in the same 2008 announcement that SpaceX has sold 14 contracts for flights on the various <a href="/wiki/Falcon_(rocket_family)" class="mw-redirect" title="Falcon (rocket family)">Falcon</a> vehicles.<sup id="cite_ref-NASA_presser_20080422_214-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-NASA_presser_20080422-214">&#91;214&#93;</a></sup> In December 2012, SpaceX announced its first two launch contracts with the <a href="/wiki/United_States_Department_of_Defense" title="United States Department of Defense">United States Department of Defense</a>. The <a href="/wiki/United_States_Air_Force" title="United States Air Force">United States Air Force</a> <a href="/wiki/Space_and_Missile_Systems_Center" title="Space and Missile Systems Center">Space and Missile Systems Center</a> awarded SpaceX two EELV-class missions: <a href="/wiki/Deep_Space_Climate_Observatory" title="Deep Space Climate Observatory">Deep Space Climate Observatory</a> (DSCOVR) and <a href="/wiki/Space_Test_Program_2" class="mw-redirect" title="Space Test Program 2">Space Test Program 2</a> (STP-2). DSCOVR was launched on a <a href="/wiki/Falcon_9" title="Falcon 9">Falcon 9</a> launch vehicle in 2015, while STP-2 was launched on a <a href="/wiki/Falcon_Heavy" title="Falcon Heavy">Falcon Heavy</a> on 25 June 2019.<sup id="cite_ref-215" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-215">&#91;215&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>In May 2015, the United States Air Force announced that the <a href="/wiki/Falcon_9_v1.1" title="Falcon 9 v1.1">Falcon 9 v1.1</a> was certified for <a href="/wiki/National_Security_Space_Launch" title="National Security Space Launch">national security space launch</a>, which allows SpaceX to contract launch services to the Air Force for any payloads classified under national security.<sup id="cite_ref-216" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-216">&#91;216&#93;</a></sup> This broke the monopoly held since 2006 by ULA over the US Air Force launches of classified payloads.<sup id="cite_ref-217" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-217">&#91;217&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>In April 2016, the U.S. Air Force awarded the first such national security launch, an $82.7 million contract to SpaceX to launch the 2nd <a href="/wiki/GPS_satellite_blocks#Block_III_satellites" title="GPS satellite blocks">GPS III</a> satellite in May 2018; this estimated cost was approximately 40% less than the estimated cost for similar previous missions.<sup id="cite_ref-218" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-218">&#91;218&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-219" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-219">&#91;219&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-220" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-220">&#91;220&#93;</a></sup> Prior to this, <a href="/wiki/United_Launch_Alliance" title="United Launch Alliance">United Launch Alliance</a> was the only provider certified to launch national security payloads.<sup id="cite_ref-fn20150527_221-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-fn20150527-221">&#91;221&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-fn20150527_221-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-fn20150527-221">&#91;221&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-wp20150536_222-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-wp20150536-222">&#91;222&#93;</a></sup> ULA did not submit a bid for the May 2018 launch.<sup id="cite_ref-223" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-223">&#91;223&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-224" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-224">&#91;224&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>In 2016 the US <a href="/wiki/National_Reconnaissance_Office" title="National Reconnaissance Office">National Reconnaissance Office</a> said it had purchased launches from SpaceX - the first (for <a href="/wiki/NROL-76" class="mw-redirect" title="NROL-76">NROL-76</a>) took place on 1 May 2017.<sup id="cite_ref-225" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-225">&#91;225&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>In March 2017 SpaceX won (vs ULA) with a bid of $96.5 million for the 3rd GPS III launch (due Feb 2019).<sup id="cite_ref-226" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-226">&#91;226&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>In March 2018, SpaceX secured an additional $290 million contract from the U.S. Air Force to launch three next-generation GPS satellites, known as GPS III. The first of these launches is expected to take place in March 2020.<sup id="cite_ref-227" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-227">&#91;227&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>In February 2019, SpaceX secured a $297 million contract from the US. Air Force to launch three national security missions, including AFSPC-44, <a href="/wiki/NROL-87" class="mw-redirect" title="NROL-87">NROL-87</a>, and <a href="/wiki/NROL-85" class="mw-redirect" title="NROL-85">NROL-85</a>, all slated to launch no earlier than FY 2021.<sup id="cite_ref-228" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-228">&#91;228&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p><br />\n</p>\n<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="International_contracts">International contracts</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=SpaceX&amp;action=edit&amp;section=30" title="Edit section: International contracts">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h3>\n<h4><span class="mw-headline" id="Kazakhstan">Kazakhstan</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=SpaceX&amp;action=edit&amp;section=31" title="Edit section: Kazakhstan">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h4>\n<p>SpaceX won a contract to launch two <a href="/wiki/Kazakhstan" title="Kazakhstan">Kazakhstan</a>\'s satellites aboard the Falcon 9 launch rocket on a rideshare with other satellites. The takeoff was scheduled for November 19, 2018. According to the Kazakh Defence and Aerospace Ministry, the launch from SpaceX would cost the country $1.3 million.<sup id="cite_ref-229" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-229">&#91;229&#93;</a></sup> The two small satellites are named KazSaySat and KazistiSat.<sup id="cite_ref-230" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-230">&#91;230&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Launch_market_competition_and_pricing_pressure">Launch market competition and pricing pressure</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=SpaceX&amp;action=edit&amp;section=32" title="Edit section: Launch market competition and pricing pressure">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>\n<div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main article: <a href="/wiki/Space_launch_market_competition" title="Space launch market competition">Space launch market competition</a></div>\n<p>SpaceX\'s low launch prices, especially for <a href="/wiki/Communication_satellite" class="mw-redirect" title="Communication satellite">communication satellites</a> flying to <a href="/wiki/Geostationary_transfer_orbit" title="Geostationary transfer orbit">geostationary</a> (GTO) orbit, have resulted in <a href="/wiki/Competition_(economics)" title="Competition (economics)">market pressure</a> on its competitors to lower their own prices.<sup id="cite_ref-A&amp;Ssmithsonian201201_29-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-A&amp;Ssmithsonian201201-29">&#91;29&#93;</a></sup> Prior to 2013, the <a href="/wiki/Space_launch_market_competition" title="Space launch market competition">openly competed</a> comsat launch market had been dominated by <a href="/wiki/Arianespace" title="Arianespace">Arianespace</a> (flying <a href="/wiki/Ariane_5" title="Ariane 5">Ariane 5</a>) and <a href="/wiki/International_Launch_Services" title="International Launch Services">International Launch Services</a> (flying <a href="/wiki/Proton_(rocket_family)" title="Proton (rocket family)">Proton</a>).<sup id="cite_ref-bbc20131203_231-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-bbc20131203-231">&#91;231&#93;</a></sup> With a published price of <span style="white-space: nowrap">US$56.5 million</span> per launch to <a href="/wiki/Low_Earth_orbit" title="Low Earth orbit">low Earth orbit</a>, "Falcon 9 rockets [were] already the cheapest in the industry. Reusable Falcon 9s could drop the price by an order of magnitude, sparking more space-based enterprise, which in turn would drop the cost of access to space still further through <a href="/wiki/Economies_of_scale" title="Economies of scale">economies of scale</a>."<sup id="cite_ref-fp20131209_232-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-fp20131209-232">&#91;232&#93;</a></sup> SpaceX has publicly indicated that if they are successful with developing the <a href="/wiki/SpaceX_reusable_rocket" class="mw-redirect" title="SpaceX reusable rocket">reusable technology</a>, launch <a href="/wiki/Market_price" class="mw-redirect" title="Market price">prices</a> in the <span style="white-space: nowrap">US$5 to 7 million</span> range for the reusable Falcon 9 are possible.<sup id="cite_ref-ps20140114_233-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ps20140114-233">&#91;233&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>In 2014, SpaceX had won nine contracts out of 20 that were openly competed worldwide in 2014 at commercial launch service providers.<sup id="cite_ref-sn20150112_234-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-sn20150112-234">&#91;234&#93;</a></sup> Space media reported that SpaceX had "already begun to take market share" from Arianespace.<sup id="cite_ref-sn20141120_235-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-sn20141120-235">&#91;235&#93;</a></sup> Arianespace has requested that European governments provide additional <a href="/wiki/Subsidy" title="Subsidy">subsidies</a> to face the competition from SpaceX.<sup id="cite_ref-aw20140211_236-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-aw20140211-236">&#91;236&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-sn20140414_237-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-sn20140414-237">&#91;237&#93;</a></sup> European <a href="/wiki/Comparison_of_communication_satellite_operators" title="Comparison of communication satellite operators">satellite operators</a> are pushing the <a href="/wiki/European_Space_Agency" title="European Space Agency">ESA</a> to reduce <a href="/wiki/Ariane_5" title="Ariane 5">Ariane 5</a> and the future <a href="/wiki/Ariane_6" title="Ariane 6">Ariane 6</a> rocket launch prices as a result of competition from SpaceX. According to one <a href="/wiki/Arianespace" title="Arianespace">Arianespace</a> managing director in 2015, it was clear that "a very significant challenge [was] coming from SpaceX ... Therefore things have to change ... and the whole European industry is being restructured, consolidated, rationalised and streamlined."<sup id="cite_ref-smh20150519_238-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-smh20150519-238">&#91;238&#93;</a></sup> Jean Botti, Director of innovation for <a href="/wiki/Airbus" title="Airbus">Airbus</a> (which makes the Ariane 5) warned that "those who don\'t take <a href="/wiki/Elon_Musk" title="Elon Musk">Elon Musk</a> seriously will have a lot to worry about."<sup id="cite_ref-239" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-239">&#91;239&#93;</a></sup> In 2014, no commercial launches were booked to fly on the Russian <a href="/wiki/Proton_(rocket_family)" title="Proton (rocket family)">Proton</a> rocket.<sup id="cite_ref-sn20150112_234-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-sn20150112-234">&#91;234&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Also in 2014, SpaceX capabilities and pricing began to affect the market for launch of US military payloads. For nearly a decade the large US launch provider <a href="/wiki/United_Launch_Alliance" title="United Launch Alliance">United Launch Alliance</a> (ULA) had faced no competition for military launches.<sup id="cite_ref-lat20141125_240-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-lat20141125-240">&#91;240&#93;</a></sup> Without this competition, launch costs by the U.S. provider rose to over $400 million.<sup id="cite_ref-241" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-241">&#91;241&#93;</a></sup> The ULA monopoly ended when SpaceX began to compete for national security launches. At a side-by-side comparison, SpaceX\'s launch costs for commercial missions are considerably lower at $62&#160;million.<sup id="cite_ref-242" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-242">&#91;242&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>In 2015, anticipating a slump in domestic military and spy launches, ULA stated that it would go out of business unless it won commercial satellite launch orders.<sup id="cite_ref-243" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-243">&#91;243&#93;</a></sup> To that end, ULA announced a major restructuring of processes and workforce in order to decrease launch costs by half.<sup id="cite_ref-dbj20141016_244-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-dbj20141016-244">&#91;244&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-lat20141212_245-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-lat20141212-245">&#91;245&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>In 2017, SpaceX had 45% global market share for awarded commercial launch contracts, the estimate for 2018 is about 65% as of July 2018.<sup id="cite_ref-246" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-246">&#91;246&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>On January 11, 2019, SpaceX issued a statement announcing it would lay off 10% of its workforce, in order to help finance the Starship and Starlink projects.<sup id="cite_ref-247" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-247">&#91;247&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="See_also">See also</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=SpaceX&amp;action=edit&amp;section=33" title="Edit section: See also">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class="div-col columns column-width" style="-moz-column-width: 30em; -webkit-column-width: 30em; column-width: 30em;">\n<ul><li><a href="/wiki/Blue_Origin" title="Blue Origin">Blue Origin</a></li>\n<li><a href="/wiki/List_of_Falcon_9_and_Falcon_Heavy_launches" title="List of Falcon 9 and Falcon Heavy launches">List of Falcon 9 and Falcon Heavy launches</a></li>\n<li><a href="/wiki/Colonization_of_Mars" title="Colonization of Mars">Colonization of Mars</a></li>\n<li><a href="/wiki/Human_mission_to_Mars" title="Human mission to Mars">Human mission to Mars</a></li>\n<li><a href="/wiki/NewSpace" title="NewSpace">NewSpace</a></li>\n<li><a href="/wiki/Private_spaceflight" title="Private spaceflight">Private spaceflight</a></li>\n<li><a href="/wiki/SpaceX_Mars_transportation_infrastructure" title="SpaceX Mars transportation infrastructure">SpaceX Mars transportation infrastructure</a></li></ul>\n</div>\n<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="References">References</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=SpaceX&amp;action=edit&amp;section=34" title="Edit section: References">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class="reflist columns references-column-width" style="-moz-column-width: 30em; The implementation was done without adequate screening or testing of the industrial grade part, without regard to the manufacturer\xe2\x80\x99s recommendations for a 4:1 factor of safety when using their industrial grade part in an application, and without proper modeling or adequate load testing of the part under predicted flight conditions.
